text: Mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 16b is a type of autosomal recessive disease and also falls under the broader category of mitochondrial DNA depletion syndromes. It specifically is a condition that arises due to autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by childhood onset of progressive neuroophthalmic manifestations, including optic atrophy, mixed polyneuropathy, spinal and cerebellar ataxia, and generalized chorea. These symptoms have a material basis in a homozygous mutation in the POLG2 gene located on chromosome 17q23. Additionally, mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 16b is exactly synonymous with mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 16B (neuroophthalmic type) and has an exact match in the OMIM database with the identifier OMIM:619425.

Mitochondrial DNA Depletion Syndrome 17 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, and it falls within the broader category of mitochondrial DNA depletion syndromes. It is also characterized by its material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. This specific syndrome is defined as a mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome that presents in childhood with symptoms such as encephalopathy, stroke-like episodes, lactic acidosis, hypocitrullinemia, and multiple mitochondrial oxidative phosphorylation deficiencies. These symptoms are due to a homozygous mutation in the MRM2 gene located on chromosome 7p22.3, leading to a phenotype that is similar to MELAS syndrome. Additionally, Mitochondrial DNA Depletion Syndrome 17 has an exact match in the OMIM database with the identifier OMIM:618567.

Mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 18 is a type of mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease, which also falls under the category of conditions that have a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by early onset progressive weakness, atrophy of the distal limb muscles, and multiple mitochondrial oxidative phosphorylation deficiencies, with this condition having its material basis in homozygous mutation in the SLC25A21 gene on chromosome 14q11.3. Additionally, mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 18 exactly matches OMIM:618811.

Mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 19 is a type of mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome, and it also falls under the category of autosomal recessive diseases. This specific syndrome is defined by a mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome that originates from a compound heterozygous mutation in the SLC25A10 gene on chromosome 17q25.3. Additionally, it has an exact match with the identifier OMIM:618972. This syndrome is a form of autosomal recessive inheritance with a material basis.

Mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 20 (MNGIE type) is a specific type of autosomal recessive disease and a form of mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome, which is defined by a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in certain autosomal recessive inheritances. This syndrome is characterized by a variable neurogastrointestinal encephalopathy that includes severe gastrointestinal dysmotility, neurogenic bladder, muscle weakness and atrophy, headaches, stroke-like episodes, seizures, pyramidal signs, and learning difficulties or cognitive decline. The cause of this syndrome is identified as compound heterozygous mutations in the LIG3 gene located on chromosome 17q12. Additionally, mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 20 is precisely matched with the OMIM database entry 619780, indicating its recognition and categorization within genetic research databases.

Xanthinuria Type I is a type of xanthinuria characterized by an isolated deficiency of xanthine dehydrogenase that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the XDH gene on chromosome 2p23. Furthermore, it has the exact synonym XAN1.

Xanthinuria Type II is a subtype of xanthinuria. It is defined as a xanthinuria characterized by a deficiency of xanthine dehydrogenase and aldehyde oxidase. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the MOCOS gene located on chromosome 18q12. Additionally, Xanthinuria Type II is precisely referred to by the synonym XAN2.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 70 (HSP70), also known precisely as SPG70 and autosomal recessive spastic paraplegia 70, is classified as a type of hereditary spastic paraplegia and falls within the broader category of autosomal recessive diseases. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and manifests with an onset during infancy. Specifically, HSP70 is defined as a hereditary spastic paraplegia that begins in infancy with motor delays and walking difficulties due to lower limb spasticity, resulting from compound heterozygous mutations in the MARS1 gene located on chromosome 12q13.3. Additionally, HSP70 is precisely matched in the medical literature with the identifier OMIM:620323.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 79a (SPG79A), also known as autosomal dominant spastic paraplegia 79A, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of hereditary spastic paraplegia. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally stems from autosomal dominant inheritance. The disease is defined as a hereditary spastic paraplegia marked by a gradual progression of cerebellar or sensory ataxia and spasticity of the lower limbs, which arises from a heterozygous mutation in the UCHL1 gene located on chromosome 4p13. Hereditary spastic paraplegia 79a is exactly matched with the OMIM database entry 620221.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 87 (HSP87) is categorized as a type of autosomal recessive disease, specifically falling under the broader category of hereditary spastic paraplegia. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and begins its existence during a period that encompasses both infantile onset and childhood onset. HSP87 is defined by the infantile or early childhood onset of lower limb spasticity, which is due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the TMEM63C gene located on chromosome 14q24.3. This condition is also referred to by its exact synonyms, SPG87 and autosomal recessive spastic paraplegia 87, and has an exact match in the OMIM database with the identifier OMIM:619966.

Hereditary Spastic Paraplegia 88 (HSP88) is a type of Hereditary Spastic Paraplegia and an autosomal dominant disease, which means it has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is also characterized by an onset that begins during infancy or early childhood, a period that encompasses both infantile and childhood onset. HSP88 is defined as a hereditary spastic paraplegia characterized by the infantile or early childhood onset of lower limb spasticity, which slowly progresses with variable severity. This condition is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the KPNA3 gene located on chromosome 13q14.2. Additionally, HSP88 is exactly synonymous with SPG88 and autosomal dominant spastic paraplegia 88, and it exactly matches OMIM:620106.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 89 (SPG89), also known as autosomal recessive spastic paraplegia 89, is a type of autosomal recessive disease, and a specific form of hereditary spastic paraplegia. This condition is characterized by its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and typically begins during infancy or early childhood, marking a period that combines infantile onset with childhood onset. It is defined by lower limb spasticity that arises from a homozygous mutation in the AMFR gene on chromosome 16q13. Furthermore, SPG89 is precisely identified in the OMIM database under the entry OMIM:620379.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 90a (SPG90A), also known as autosomal dominant spastic paraplegia 90A, is a type of hereditary spastic paraplegia and an autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized as a hereditary spastic paraplegia that fundamentally has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, this condition is defined by motor impairment and progressive lower limb spasticity, which is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the SPTSSA gene located on chromosome 14q13.1. Additionally, hereditary spastic paraplegia 90a has an exact match with OMIM:620416 in the medical literature.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 90b (SPG90B), also known as autosomal recessive spastic paraplegia 90B, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of hereditary spastic paraplegia. It is defined as a hereditary spastic paraplegia characterized by motor impairment and progressive lower limb spasticity, which has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the SPTSSA gene located on chromosome 14q13.1. This condition is related to something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance and has an exact match with OMIM:620417.

Mitochondrial Complex V ATP Synthase Deficiency Nuclear Type 4A, also known exactly as MC5DN4A and matching OMIM:620358, is a type of autosomal dominant disease. It specifically belongs to the group of Mitochondrial Complex V ATP Synthase Deficiency Nuclear Type 4 and is defined by having a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. This condition is characterized by an infantile onset, beginning with poor feeding and failure to thrive that may either spontaneously resolve or progress to developmental delay with impaired intellectual development and movement abnormalities. The onset of this disease occurs during infancy.

Mitochondrial complex V ATP synthase deficiency nuclear type 4b is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a subtype of mitochondrial complex V ATP synthase deficiency nuclear type 4. It is characterized by its onset at birth, including symptoms such as horizontal and vertical nystagmus, abnormal primitive reflexes, and tonus dysregulation, leading to fatal encephalopathy. The condition has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is known to manifest during congenital onset. It also has the exact synonym MC5DN4B and is matched exactly with OMIM:615228.

Mitochondrial complex V ATP synthase deficiency nuclear type 5 (MC5DN5) is a type of autosomal recessive disease, specifically a type of mitochondrial complex V ATP synthase deficiency. It is characterized as a condition that has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. The definition of this condition specifies that it is a mitochondrial complex V (ATP synthase) deficiency that results from a homozygous mutation in the ATP5F1D gene located on chromosome 19p13.3. Furthermore, mitochondrial complex V ATP synthase deficiency nuclear type 5 is precisely matched with the OMIM database entry OMIM:618120.

Mitochondrial complex V ATP synthase deficiency nuclear type 7, also known exactly as MC5DN7, is a specific type of autosomal recessive disease and a form of mitochondrial complex V ATP synthase deficiency. This condition is characterized by having a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined by a mitochondrial complex V (ATP synthase) deficiency that results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ATP5PO gene located on chromosome 21q22.11. Additionally, mitochondrial complex V ATP synthase deficiency nuclear type 7 exactly matches the OMIM database entry 620359.

Spinocerebellar ataxia with axonal neuropathy type 3, also exactly known as SCAN3, autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia with axonal neuropathy 3, and spinocerebellar ataxia with axonal neuropathy 3, is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia. It is defined as an autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia characterized by the onset of a slowly progressive axonal peripheral neuropathy in the first decade of life, evident in distal muscle weakness and atrophy, and distal sensory impairment. This is followed by cerebellar ataxia and atrophy, which has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the COA7 gene on chromosome 1p32.3.

Carpal tunnel syndrome 1 (CTS1) is a type of carpal tunnel syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, it is defined as a carpal tunnel syndrome that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the TTR gene on chromosome 18q12.1.

Carpal tunnel syndrome 2, also known exactly as CTS2, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a subtype of carpal tunnel syndrome. It is characterized by a condition that necessarily has its material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, carpal tunnel syndrome 2 is defined as a carpal tunnel syndrome that arises from a heterozygous mutation in the COMP gene located on chromosome 19p13.11.

Yoon Bellen neurodevelopmental syndrome is a type of syndrome that falls under the category of autosomal recessive diseases, specifically ones that have a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by onset in the first decade of life, presenting highly variable neurodevelopmental phenotypes including global developmental delay, intellectual disability, seizures, hearing and visual problems, and ataxia, all of which have a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the OGDHL gene located on chromosome 10q11.23. Yoon Bellen neurodevelopmental syndrome is also precisely known by its exact synonym YOBELN and has an exact match in the OMIM database with the identifier OMIM:619701.

The neurodevelopmental disorder with dysmorphic facies and thin corpus callosum, also known precisely as NEDDFAC, is categorized as a type of autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder. It is defined by characteristics such as global developmental delay, impaired intellectual development with limited or non-existent speech and language, dysmorphic facial features, and abnormalities in the corpus callosum. This disorder has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the SUPT16H gene located on chromosome 14q11.2. Additionally, it is exactly matched with OMIM:619480 in medical classifications.

Chromosome 1p36.33 duplication syndrome is a type of chromosomal duplication syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease, which specifically involves a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. This syndrome is characterized by cardiomyopathy, corneal clouding or cataracts, hyperlactacidemia, and perinatal death due to a heterozygous duplication within the ATAD3 gene cluster on chromosome 1p36.33, resulting in ATAD3A/ATAD3C gene fusion. Common symptoms also include hypotonia, encephalopathy, seizures, and white matter abnormalities. It is precisely identified as CHROMOSOME 1p36.33 DUPLICATION SYNDROME, ATAD3 GENE CLUSTER, AUTOSOMAL DOMINANT and has exact matches in medical databases, including OMIM with the identifier 618815, ORDO with the identifier 656279, and UMLS_CUI with the code C5394150.

Early onset epilepsy 2 (EPEO2), which has an exact match with OMIM:618832, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a form of epilepsy. It specifically arises from a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. This condition is characterized by an onset ranging from neonatal to childhood, encompassing infantile, neonatal, and childhood onsets. The definition of early onset epilepsy 2 highlights it as an epilepsy characterized by neonatal to childhood onset of generalized tonic-clonic seizures, which results from a heterozygous mutation in the SETD1A gene on chromosome 16p11.2.

Early onset epilepsy 3 (EPEO3) is a type of autosomal dominant disease, which is a category of epilepsy. Specifically, it is characterized by an onset that begins during a period that includes infantile and childhood stages. This condition is known for having a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. Early onset epilepsy 3 is defined by its infantile or childhood onset of various types of seizures, which are accompanied by variable global developmental delay and intellectual disability. These symptoms are due to a heterozygous mutation in the ATP6V0C gene located on chromosome 16p13.3. Additionally, early onset epilepsy 3 is precisely matched with the OMIM database entry 620465.

Zaki syndrome is a type of autosomal recessive disease and syndrome, which specifically has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by developmental delay, progressive microcephaly, short stature, and dysmorphic features including sparse scalp hair, cupped ears, wide nose and mouth, short philtrum, and high-arched palate. This syndrome has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the WLS gene on chromosome 1p31.3, and it may also present with additional variable features including ocular, skeletal, cardiac, and renal anomalies. Zaki syndrome has an exact match with OMIM:619648.

Childhood onset neurodegeneration with brain atrophy is a type of neurodegenerative disease that is also classified as an autosomal dominant disease. It is defined as a neurodegenerative disease characterized by loss of motor and cognitive skills between ages 2 and 7 years, with progressive cerebral and cerebellar atrophy, leading to the inability to walk, absence of language, and profound intellectual disability. This condition has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the UBTF gene on chromosome 17q21.31. It is exactly synonymous with CONDBA and childhood-onset motor and cognitive regression syndrome with extrapyramidal movement disorder.

Furthermore, childhood onset neurodegeneration with brain atrophy has exact matches with several medical databases and coding systems, including GARD:13658, OMIM:617672, ORDO:500180, SNOMEDCT_US_2023_03_01:1167373005, and UMLS_CUI codes C4540086 and C5567227.

Smarcb1 deficient renal medullary carcinoma is a type of renal cell carcinoma that develops in the renal medulla, indicating it is a kind of disease located in the renal medulla. This carcinoma is also known by several exact synonyms, including RMC, kidney medullary carcinoma, medullary carcinoma of the kidney, medullary renal cell carcinoma, and renal medullary carcinoma. Moreover, smarcb1 deficient renal medullary carcinoma is precisely matched to multiple databases and identifiers, including GARD:13175, NCI:C7572, ORDO:319319, SNOMEDCT_US_2023_10_01:765095002, and UMLS_CUI:C4049328.

Diphthamide deficiency syndrome is a complex condition classified as an autosomal recessive disease, an amino acid metabolic disorder, and is notably characterized by a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It exhibits phenotypes such as global developmental delay, short stature, and sparse hair. The syndrome is defined as an inherited metabolic disorder marked by global developmental delay, short stature, dysmorphic craniofacial features, and sparse hair, which results from deficient diphthamidylation of the eukaryotic translation Elongation Factor 2 protein (gene: EEF2). It is synonymously known as DEDSSH, craniofacial dysplasia-short stature-ectodermal anomalies-intellectual disability syndrome, and developmental delay with short stature, dysmorphic facial features, and sparse hair. Furthermore, diphthamide deficiency syndrome is precisely matched in medical databases, identified as OMIM:PS616901 and ORDO:459061.

Diphthamide deficiency syndrome 1 is a type of diphthamide deficiency syndrome characterized by a genetic basis involving homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the DPH1 gene located on chromosome 17p13.3. It is also known by several exact synonyms, including DEDSSH1, DPH1 syndrome, Loucks-Innes syndrome, and developmental delay with short stature, dysmorphic facial features, and sparse hair 1. Additionally, it has an exact match with OMIM:616901.

Diphthamide deficiency syndrome 2 is a type of diphthamide deficiency syndrome that is defined as a diphthamide deficiency syndrome with a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the DPH2 gene located on chromosome 1p34.1. This condition has exact synonyms, including DEDSSH2 and developmental delay with short stature, dysmorphic facial features, and sparse hair 2. Furthermore, diphthamide deficiency syndrome 2 exactly matches OMIM:620062.

The Neurodevelopmental Disorder with Short Stature Prominent Forehead and Feeding Difficulties (NEDSFF) is classified as a type of Diphthamide Deficiency Syndrome. This disorder encompasses several phenotypes, including absent speech, difficulty walking, feeding difficulties, and a delayed ability to walk. It is defined as a Diphthamide Deficiency Syndrome characterized by its symptoms, which also include difficulty walking and absent speech, resulting from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the DPH5 gene located on chromosome 1p21.2. Furthermore, NEDSFF is precisely matched with the OMIM entry 620070.

Schwannomatosis 1 is a type of schwannomatosis, which is defined as a schwannomatosis that has its material basis in germline heterozygous mutation in the SMARCB1 gene on chromosome 22q11.23. It is also broadly synonymous with neurofibromatosis 3 and has exact synonyms including SMARCB1-related schwannomatosis and SWN1. Moreover, Schwannomatosis 1 has exact matches with several medical identifiers: NCI:C186703, OMIM:162091, and UMLS_CUI:C5670707.

Schwannomatosis 2 is a type of schwannomatosis that is defined as a schwannomatosis with its material basis in a germline heterozygous mutation in the LZTR1 gene on chromosome 22q11.2. It is broadly synonymous with neurofibromatosis 3 and exactly synonymous with LZTR1-related schwannomatosis as well as SWN2. Furthermore, Schwannomatosis 2 has exact matches with NCI:C186704, OMIM:615670, and UMLS_CUI:C5670708.

Spinal neurofibromatosis is a type of neurofibromatosis 1, which is characterized by bilateral neurofibromas of all spinal roots. This condition is also known as FNSF, SNF, or familial spinal neurofibromatosis and has an exact match with OMIM:162210. Furthermore, it is a kind of disease that affects some spinal nerve root.

Watson syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of RASopathy, which also falls under the category of conditions that have a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a RASopathy characterized by pulmonic stenosis, cafe-au-lait macules, decreased intellectual ability, and short stature, which is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the NF1 gene on chromosome 17q11.2. Additionally, Watson syndrome exactly matches with the OMIM identifier 193520.

Legius syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of RASopathy. It is characterized by a condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, Legius syndrome is defined as a RASopathy characterized by multiple cafe-au-lait macules and possible skin fold freckling without neurofibromas, optic gliomas, or Lisch nodules, which has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the SPRED1 gene on chromosome 15q14. It is also known by exact synonyms such as LGSS, NF1-like syndrome, and neurofibromatosis type 1-like syndrome. Furthermore, Legius syndrome has exact matches with several databases and classifications, including GARD:10714, MESH:C548032, NCI:C176941, OMIM:611431, ORDO:137605, SNOMEDCT_US_2023_03_01:703541007, and UMLS_CUI:C1969623.

Mitochondrial complex IV deficiency nuclear type 23, also known exactly as MC4DN23, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a cytochrome c oxidase deficiency disease. It is characterized by its nature of being an autosomal recessive inheritance disease. Specifically, this condition is defined as a cytochrome-c oxidase deficiency disease that manifests with an infantile onset encephalopathy, which has its material basis in homozygous mutation in the COX11 gene located on chromosome 17q22. Additionally, mitochondrial complex IV deficiency nuclear type 23 is precisely matched with OMIM:620275 and UMLS_CUI:C5830322 in medical databases.

Parkinson's disease 25 is a form of early-onset Parkinson's disease that is categorized as an autosomal recessive disease and is also recognized for its relation to autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as an early-onset Parkinson's disease with mild to moderately impaired intellectual development, resulting from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PTPA gene on chromosome 9q34.11. Parkinson's disease 25 is precisely identified as PARK25 and autosomal recessive early-onset Parkinson disease 25 with impaired intellectual development in synonym terms. Additionally, it has an exact match in the OMIM database with the identifier OMIM:620482.

Dopamine transporter deficiency syndrome (DTDS) is a type of autosomal genetic disease and movement disease, which specifically has a material basis in autosomal inheritance. It is defined as a movement disease characterized by parkinsonism-dystonia, including symptoms such as tremor, progressive bradykinesia, and dystonic posturing. This condition is caused by a mutation in the SLC6A3 gene located on chromosome 5p15.33.

Atypical dopamine transporter deficiency syndrome (DTDS) is a specific kind of dopamine transporter deficiency syndrome. This syndrome is unique because it encompasses conditions that, at the very least, are rooted in both adult onset and juvenile onset. It is defined by a normal psychomotor development during early childhood, with the onset of parkinsonism-dystonia occurring from late childhood into adulthood. Additionally, atypical dopamine transporter deficiency syndrome is precisely synonymous with atypical DTDS.

Classic dopamine transporter deficiency syndrome (classic DTDS), also known exactly as PKDYS1 and infantile parkinsonism-dystonia 1, is a type of dopamine transporter deficiency syndrome, which falls under the category of autosomal recessive diseases. It is characterized by an infantile onset of chorea, dystonia, ballismus, and orolingual dyskinesia, followed by progressive parkinsonism-dystonia. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the SLC6A3 gene on chromosome 5p15.33, and it is noteworthy for an elevated homovanillic acid to hydroxyindoleacetic acid ratio in cerebrospinal fluid. Classic DTDS is not only a type of autosomal recessive disease but also signifies conditions with material bases in autosomal recessive inheritance and infantile onset. It is broadly matched with OMIM:PS613135 and has exact matches with various databases, including GARD:10484, MESH:C567730, NCI:C129866, OMIM:613135, ORDO:238455, SNOMEDCT_US_2023_03_01:722763000, and UMLS_CUI:C2751067.

Infantile parkinsonism dystonia 2 is recognized as a type of autosomal recessive disease and a movement disease, which fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and infantile onset. This disease is defined as a movement disorder characterized by parkinsonism, dystonia, poor fine motor skills, and autonomic dysfunction including abnormal sweating, cold extremities, and poor sleep. This condition is due to a homozygous mutation in the SLC18A2 gene located on chromosome 10q25.3. It is synonymously known as Brain dopamine-serotonin vesicular transport disease and PKDYS2. Regarding its classification and identifiers, infantile parkinsonism dystonia 2 matches broadly with OMIM:PS613135 and exactly with GARD:13594, OMIM:618049, SNOMEDCT_US_2023_03_01:717942003, and UMLS_CUI codes C4303546 and C4747991.

Mitochondrial complex IV deficiency nuclear type 1 (MC4DN1) is a type of autosomal recessive disease that is also known as a type of COX deficiency benign infantile mitochondrial myopathy. It is characterized by being a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, this condition is defined as a COX deficiency, benign infantile mitochondrial myopathy that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the SURF1 gene on chromosome 9q34.2. Moreover, MC4DN1 has exact matches with NCI:C176895, OMIM:220110, and UMLS_CUI:C5435656.

Mitochondrial Complex IV Deficiency Nuclear Type 3, also known exactly as MC4DN3, is a specific type of autosomal recessive disease that falls under the category of benign infantile mitochondrial myopathy with a COX deficiency. This condition notably has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance, particularly through homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the COX10 gene located on chromosome 17p12. Additionally, Mitochondrial Complex IV Deficiency Nuclear Type 3 is precisely matched to OMIM:619046 and UMLS_CUI:C5436682 in medical databases.

Mitochondrial complex IV deficiency nuclear type 4 (MC4DN4) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a form of COX deficiency benign infantile mitochondrial myopathy. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. This condition is specifically defined as a COX deficiency, benign infantile mitochondrial myopathy that results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the SCO1 gene located on chromosome 17p13.1. MC4DN4 is exactly matched with OMIM:619048 and UMLS_CUI:C5436683 in medical databases.

Mitochondrial Complex IV Deficiency Nuclear Type 7, which has the exact synonym MC4DN7, is classified as a type of autosomal recessive disease, as well as a type of COX deficiency benign infantile mitochondrial myopathy. Additionally, it is described as a condition that inherently involves some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined specifically as a COX deficiency, benign infantile mitochondrial myopathy characterized by a homozygous mutation in the COX6B1 gene located on chromosome 19q13.12. Furthermore, Mitochondrial Complex IV Deficiency Nuclear Type 7 has exact matches in medical databases, including OMIM with the identifier 619051 and UMLS_CUI with the code C5436685.

Mitochondrial Complex IV Deficiency Nuclear Type 8 (MC4DN8), which has exact matches in OMIM:619052 and UMLS_CUI:C5436689, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and can also be referred to as a benign infantile mitochondrial myopathy known as COX deficiency. This condition, which has its material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance, is characterized by a normal early development followed by the onset of a slowly progressive decline in neurologic function in the first decade of life. This decline results in gait difficulties, spasticity, dysarthria, hypotonia, and variable intellectual disability, all due to homozygous mutations in the TACO1 gene located on chromosome 17q23.3.

Mitochondrial complex IV deficiency nuclear type 10, also known as MC4DN10, is classified as an autosomal recessive disease. It falls under the category of COX deficiency benign infantile mitochondrial myopathy and is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. This condition is defined by a homozygous mutation in the COX14 gene located on chromosome 12q13.12. Additionally, mitochondrial complex IV deficiency nuclear type 10 is precisely matched with OMIM:619053 and UMLS_CUI:C5436692.

Mitochondrial complex IV deficiency nuclear type 11 (MC4DN11) is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which is also known as a benign infantile mitochondrial myopathy due to COX deficiency. It is characterized by having a material basis in homozygous mutation in the COX20 gene located on chromosome 1q44. This condition is precisely cataloged as OMIM:619054 and UMLS_CUI:C5436694 in medical databases.

Mitochondrial complex IV deficiency nuclear type 12, also known exactly as MC4DN12, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of COX deficiency benign infantile mitochondrial myopathy. This condition is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. More precisely, it is defined as a COX deficiency, benign infantile mitochondrial myopathy that results from a homozygous mutation in the PET100 gene located on chromosome 19p13.2. Mitochondrial complex IV deficiency nuclear type 12 is precisely identified in medical databases with the exact matches to OMIM:619055 and UMLS_CUI:C5436695.

Mitochondrial complex IV deficiency nuclear type 14, which has the exact synonym MC4DN14, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of COX deficiency benign infantile mitochondrial myopathy. This condition is characterized as an autosomal recessive disease with a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a COX deficiency, benign infantile mitochondrial myopathy that has its material basis in compound heterozygous mutation in the COA3 gene on chromosome 17q21.2. Moreover, mitochondrial complex IV deficiency nuclear type 14 precisely matches with OMIM:619058 and UMLS_CUI:C5436710 in medical databases.

Mitochondrial complex IV deficiency nuclear type 15, which has the exact synonym MC4DN15, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of cox deficiency benign infantile mitochondrial myopathy. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance, particularly through a homozygous mutation in the COX8A gene located on chromosome 11q13.1. This condition is precisely identified in medical databases with an exact match to OMIM:619059 and UMLS_CUI:C5436712.

Mitochondrial complex IV deficiency nuclear type 16, also known by its exact synonym MC4DN16, is categorized as a type of autosomal recessive disease, specifically a benign infantile mitochondrial myopathy termed COX deficiency. This condition is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance, particularly through a homozygous mutation in the COX4I1 gene located on chromosome 16q24.1. Additionally, mitochondrial complex IV deficiency nuclear type 16 is precisely matched with OMIM:619060 and UMLS_CUI:C5436714 in medical databases.

Mitochondrial complex IV deficiency nuclear type 17, also known as MC4DN17, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a benign infantile mitochondrial myopathy characterized by COX deficiency. This condition is notably a type of disorder that essentially requires autosomal recessive inheritance for its materialization. It is precisely defined by a COX deficiency, benign infantile mitochondrial myopathy that is grounded on homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the APOPT1 gene located on chromosome 14q32.33. Furthermore, mitochondrial complex IV deficiency nuclear type 17 is exactly matched with OMIM entry 619061 and UMLS_CUI C5436718, indicating its recognition and classification in these medical databases.

Mitochondrial complex IV deficiency nuclear type 18, which has the exact synonym MC4DN18, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of COX deficiency benign infantile mitochondrial myopathy. This condition is characterized as a COX deficiency, benign infantile mitochondrial myopathy that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the COX6A2 gene located on chromosome 16p11.2. It is also defined by its relation to autosomal recessive inheritance. Further, mitochondrial complex IV deficiency nuclear type 18 has exact matches in medical databases, including OMIM with the identifier 619062 and UMLS_CUI with the code C5436720.

Mitochondrial Complex IV Deficiency Nuclear Type 19 (MC4DN19), also known as a COX deficiency, benign infantile mitochondrial myopathy, is a type of autosomal recessive disease. This condition is characterized by a material basis in homozygous mutation in the PET117 gene located on chromosome 20p11.23. It is categorized under autosomal recessive diseases and benign infantile mitochondrial myopathies with a COX deficiency. MC4DN19 has exact matches in medical databases, specifically OMIM:619063 and UMLS_CUI:C5436723.

Mitochondrial complex IV deficiency nuclear type 20, also known by its exact synonym MC4DN20, is a type of autosomal recessive disease. It falls under a category of COX deficiency, benign infantile mitochondrial myopathy, which has a material basis in homozygous mutation in the COX5A gene located on chromosome 15q24.2. This condition is characterized as a type of disorder that inherently involves some autosomal recessive inheritance. Furthermore, mitochondrial complex IV deficiency nuclear type 20 is precisely matched with OMIM:619064 and UMLS_CUI:C5436726 in medical databases.

Mitochondrial complex IV deficiency nuclear type 21 (MC4DN21) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and also a type of COX deficiency benign infantile mitochondrial myopathy. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, this condition is defined as a COX deficiency, benign infantile mitochondrial myopathy that has its material basis in homozygous mutation in the NDUFA4 gene on chromosome 7p21.3. MC4DN21 has exact matches with OMIM:619065 and UMLS_CUI:C5436727.

Mitochondrial complex IV deficiency nuclear type 22, also exactly known as MC4DN22, is a form of autosomal recessive disease that is a type of COX deficiency benign infantile mitochondrial myopathy. It is categorized under conditions that have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance, specifically through a homozygous mutation in the COX16 gene located on chromosome 14q24.2. Moreover, mitochondrial complex IV deficiency nuclear type 22 exactly matches with OMIM:619355 and UMLS_CUI:C5543491 in medical databases.

Metabolic Dysfunction and Alcohol Associated Liver Disease (MetALD), also known as metabolic dysfunction and alcohol related liver disease, is a type of steatotic liver disease. It is defined as a steatotic liver disease characterized by at least one of the five cardiometabolic risk factors for MASLD and alcohol consumption of 140-350g/week for females or 210-420g/week for males. This disease is differentiated from MASLD by increased alcohol consumption and from ALD by the presence of one or more of the MASLD cardiometabolic risk factors.

Schinzel Giedion Syndrome (SGS), also known as Schinzel-Giedion Midface Retraction Syndrome, is characterized as a type of autosomal dominant disease and a form of ectodermal dysplasia. It is defined as an ectodermal dysplasia that presents distinctive facial features, hydronephrosis, severe developmental delay, typical skeletal malformations, genital and cardiac anomalies, and an increased tumor prevalence. The syndrome has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the SETBP1 gene located on chromosome 18q12.3, signifying an autosomal dominant inheritance. Schinzel Giedion Syndrome has been exactly matched with several identifiers: GARD:117, MESH:C536632, NCI:C129308, OMIM:269150, ORDO:798, SNOMEDCT_US_2023_03_01:18899000, and UMLS_CUI:C0265227.

Inflammatory poikiloderma with hair abnormalities and acral keratoses is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a type of skin disease, specifically something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by mottled hyper- and hypopigmentation of the skin, sparse scalp hair and eyelashes, sparse or absent eyebrows, and palmoplantar keratoses, with a material basis in a homozygous mutation in the LTV1 gene on chromosome 6q24.2. This condition is also known by its exact synonyms IPHAK, LIPHAK, and LIPHAK syndrome. Furthermore, it has exact matches in medical databases, identified by OMIM:620199 and UMLS_CUI:C5774293.

Polyhydramnios megalencephaly and symptomatic epilepsy (PMSE) is a syndrome characterized by polyhydramnios, distinctive craniofacial features, infantile-onset epilepsy, hypotonia, macrocephaly, and global developmental delay. It is an autosomal recessive disease with a material basis in homozygous mutation in the STRADA gene on chromosome 17q23.3. The existence of PMSE starts during fetal onset. PMSE is also known by its exact synonyms PMSE syndrome, and Pretzel syndrome. Furthermore, PMSE has exact matches in various medical databases and classification systems, including GARD:12913, MESH:C567020, OMIM:611087, ORDO:500533, SNOMEDCT_US_2023_03_01:1167371007, and UMLS_CUI:C1970203.

The neurodevelopmental disorder with hypotonia and speech delay, also known exactly as NEDHSS and precisely matching OMIM:620455, is categorized as a type of autosomal genetic disease, a syndrome, and something that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal inheritance. This syndrome is specifically defined as a condition characterized by global developmental delay, impaired intellectual development with poor or absent speech, and fine and gross motor delay. This condition arises from a heterozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the EIF4A2 gene located on chromosome 3q27.3.

Neurodevelopmental disorder with dysmorphic facies and behavioral abnormalities is a type of autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder. This disorder is defined as an autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the SRSF1 gene on chromosome 17q22. It has the exact synonym NEDFBA and an exact match with OMIM:620489.

Neurodevelopmental disorder with dysmorphic facies and distal limb anomalies is a type of autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder, which is defined as an autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder characterized by developmental delay, intellectual disability, speech delay, postnatal microcephaly, and dysmorphic features. This condition has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the BPTF gene on chromosome 17q24.2. Furthermore, it has an exact synonym, NEDDFL, and an exact match with OMIM:617755.

Chromosome 16p11.2 deletion syndrome 593 kb is a type of chromosomal deletion syndrome, also known as Proximal 16p11.2 microdeletion syndrome. It is defined as a chromosomal deletion syndrome characterized by language delay and mild intellectual disability, which has a material basis in the partial deletion of a contiguous 593-kb region of chromosome 16p11.2 (chr16:29.5-30.1 Mb). This syndrome is categorized under ICD10CM:Q93.5, indicating a broader match. It has exact matches in several medical databases and registries, including GARD:10740, OMIM:611913, ORDO:261197, and UMLS_CUI with identifiers C3150154 and C4273657.

Mitchell syndrome is an autosomal dominant and peroxisomal disease. It is defined as a peroxisomal disease characterized by progressive episodic demyelination, sensorimotor polyneuropathy, and hearing loss, which is due to a heterozygous mutation in the ACOX1 gene located on chromosome 17q25.1. This syndrome is an example of a condition that inherently has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Moreover, Mitchell syndrome is exactly matched with OMIM:618960, ORDO:631248, and UMLS_CUI:C5394554.

Retinal Macular Dystrophy 2 is a specific type of Retinal Macular Dystrophy. It is defined as a retinal macular dystrophy characterized by a slowly progressive "bull's eye" maculopathy, mild visual impairment, and central scotomata, which is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the PROM1 gene located on chromosome 4p15.32. The condition is also exactly synonymous with MCDR2. Furthermore, Retinal Macular Dystrophy 2 is precisely matched with several medical databases and coding systems: MESH (C562746), OMIM (608051), ORDO (319640), SNOMEDCT_US_2023_03_01 (770594005), and UMLS_CUI (C4749334).

Familial multiple lipomatosis is a type of autosomal dominant disease, lipomatosis, and something that at least has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by the development of numerous encapsulated lipomas on the extremities and trunk, which is rooted in autosomal dominant inheritance. Familial multiple lipomatosis is precisely matched to several medical databases and identifiers, including GARD:12925, MESH:D000071070, OMIM:151900, ORDO:199276, and UMLS_CUI:C1275273.

Early onset vitamin B6 dependent epilepsy 4 is a type of pyridoxine dependent epilepsy, which is defined as a pyridoxine-dependent epilepsy that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ALDH7A1 gene on chromosome 5q23.2. It is exactly synonymous with AASA dehydrogenase deficiency, EPEO4, PDE-ALDH7A1, and antiquitin deficiency. Furthermore, it has an exact match with OMIM:266100.

Peeling skin syndrome 1 is a specific type of peeling skin syndrome characterized by a condition that arises due to a homozygous mutation in the CDSN gene located on chromosome 6p21.33. It is precisely identified as PSS1, generalized inflammatory peeling skin syndrome, inflammatory peeling skin syndrome, and peeling skin syndrome type B. Furthermore, peeling skin syndrome 1 is accurately matched with OMIM:270300, ORDO:263553, and UMLS_CUI codes C5679693 and C5768235.

Peeling skin syndrome 2 is a type of peeling skin syndrome characterized by a condition that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TGM5 gene on chromosome 15q15.2. It is broadly synonymous with APSS, acral peeling skin syndrome, and localized peeling skin syndrome while being exactly synonymous with PSS2. Moreover, peeling skin syndrome 2 is matched exactly with several medical identifiers: GARD:12863, MESH:C536316, OMIM:609796, ORDO:263534, SNOMEDCT_US_2023_03_01:709416009, and UMLS_CUI:C1853354.

Peeling skin syndrome 3 is a type of peeling skin syndrome that is defined by a peeling skin syndrome which has its material basis in homozygous mutation in the CHST8 gene on chromosome 19q13.11. Additionally, it is broadly synonymous with peeling skin syndrome type A and has an exact synonym of PSS3. Moreover, peeling skin syndrome 3 has a broader match with ORDO:263548 and an exact match with OMIM:616265.

Peeling skin syndrome 4 is a type of peeling skin syndrome characterized by a peeling skin syndrome that has a material basis in homozygous mutation in the CSTA gene on chromosome 3q21.1. It is broadly synonymous with AREI, autosomal recessive exfoliative ichthyosis, exfoliative ichthyosis, and ichthyosis exfoliativa. The exact synonyms for peeling skin syndrome 4 include PSS4 and ichthyosis bullosa of Siemens-like. Additionally, peeling skin syndrome 4 has exact matches with MESH:C564309 and OMIM:607936.

Peeling skin syndrome 5 is categorized as a type of peeling skin syndrome and is characterized by a peeling skin syndrome that stems from a homozygous mutation in the SERPINB8 gene located on chromosome 18q22.1. This condition is broadly synonymous with autosomal recessive exfoliative ichthyosis, exfoliative ichthyosis, and ichthyosis exfoliativa, while it is exactly synonymous with PSS5. Additionally, peeling skin syndrome 5 has an exact match in the OMIM database with the identifier 617115.

Peeling Skin Syndrome 6 is a type of Peeling Skin Syndrome and it is defined as a Peeling Skin Syndrome that has its material basis in homozygous mutation in the FLG2 gene on chromosome 1q21.3. It is broadly synonymous with Peeling Skin Syndrome Type A and has the exact synonym PSS6. Moreover, it has a broader match with ORDO:263548 and an exact match with OMIM:618084.

Plack syndrome is a type of autosomal recessive disease that also qualifies as a skin disease. It is characterized by peeling skin in association with leukonychia, acral punctate keratoses, cheilitis, and knuckle pads. The condition has a material basis in homozygous mutation in the CAST gene located on chromosome 5q15. Plack syndrome is also known by its exact synonym, "peeling skin with leukonychia, acral punctate keratoses, cheilitis, and knuckle pads." Furthermore, it is recognized across various medical databases and classifications, having exact matches in OMIM (616295), ORDO (444138), SNOMED CT US 2023_03_01 (1237509001), and UMLS CUI (C4225381).

Borrelia miyamotoi disease, also known as BMD or hard tick-borne relapsing fever, is a primary bacterial infectious disease. It has a material basis in Borrelia miyamotoi and is transmitted by tick-borne transmission, specifically through various types of ticks including the blacklegged tick (Ixodes scapularis), the western blacklegged tick (Ixodes pacificus), the taiga tick (Ixodes persulcatus), and the castor bean tick (Ixodes ricinus). The disease manifests with several symptoms such as fever, headache, chills, muscle pain, joint pain, asthenia (weakness), fatigue, and nausea. These symptoms highlight the impact of the infection on the body, sometimes leading to rarely observed relapses. Notably, Borrelia miyamotoi disease is recognized in the medical community with the identifiers SNOMEDCT_US_2023_03_01:713014002 and UMLS_CUI:C4076531, ensuring a standardized approach to its diagnosis and treatment.

Cepacia syndrome, also known exactly as CS, is defined as an opportunistic bacterial infectious disease characterized by necrotizing pneumonia, acute respiratory distress syndrome, and bacteremia. It has a material basis in the Burkholderia cepacia complex. The transmission of Cepacia syndrome occurs through various means including contact transmission, droplet spread transmission, vehicle-borne fomite transmission, and vehicle-borne ingestion transmission. This disease notably features adult respiratory distress syndrome.

Sifrim Hitz Weiss syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder characterized by developmental delay, speech delay, usually mild-to-moderate intellectual disability, and variable congenital anomalies in other systems. This condition has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the CHD4 gene on chromosome 12p13.31. It is also known by several exact synonyms, including CHD4 Neurodevelopmental Disorder, CHD4-related neurodevelopmental disorder, CHD4-related neurodevelopmental syndrome, SIFRIM-HITZ-WEISS MULTIPLE CONGENITAL ANOMALIES-MENTAL RETARDATION SYNDROME, and SIHIWES. Moreover, Sifrim Hitz Weiss syndrome precisely matches with OMIM identifier 617159 and ORDO identifier 653712.

Foveal hypoplasia 1 is classified as a type of autosomal dominant disease, retinal disease, and something that inherently has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a retinal disease characterized by foveal hypoplasia with decreased visual acuity, nystagmus, and lack of aniridia, which arises from a heterozygous mutation in the PAX6 gene on chromosome 11p13. This condition is precisely synonymous with FVH1 and foveal hypoplasia 1 with or without anterior segment anomalies and/or cataract. Additionally, it has narrower synonyms, including O'Donnell-Pappas syndrome and foveal hypoplasia-presenile cataract syndrome. Foveal hypoplasia 1 exactly matches with OMIM:136520 in the database and has narrower matches with GARD:406, ORDO:2253, and UMLS_CUI:C2931644, indicating specific references to this condition in various medical and genetic databases.

Foveal hypoplasia 2 is classified as a type of autosomal recessive disease, specifically a retinal disease, which inherently has its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a retinal disease characterized by foveal hypoplasia with decreased visual acuity and nystagmus that results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the SLC38A8 gene on chromosome 16q23.3. This condition is also frequently associated with optic nerve decussation defects and anterior segment dysgenesis. Foveal hypoplasia 2 is precisely identified by the exact synonyms FVH2 and foveal hypoplasia 2 with or without optic nerve misrouting and/or anterior segment dysgenesis. Additionally, it has narrow synonyms including FHONDA, FHONDA syndrome, and foveal hypoplasia, optic nerve decussation defects, and anterior segment dysgenesis. This condition is exactly matched with several medical identifiers: OMIM:609218, ORDO:397618, SNOMEDCT_US_2023_03_01:782754006, and UMLS_CUI:C5190596.

Aniridia 1 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and also a type of aniridia. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, Aniridia 1 is defined as an aniridia that arises from a heterozygous mutation in the PAX6 gene on chromosome 11p13, and it is often associated with additional ocular anomalies. Furthermore, Aniridia 1 exactly matches with OMIM:106210.

Long QT Syndrome 16 (LQT16) is a type of Long QT Syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by perinatal onset of markedly prolonged corrected QT (QTc) interval, 2:1 atrioventricular (AV) block, and bradycardia or ventricular tachycardia (torsades de pointes). This condition has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the CALM3 gene on chromosome 19q13.32, making it a type of disease that inherently has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. Common issues associated with LQT16 include syncope, cardiac arrest, and sudden death. It is also referred to by its exact synonym LQT16 and matches the OMIM entry 618782.

Arrhythmogenic left ventricular cardiomyopathy is a type of intrinsic cardiomyopathy characterized by a hypokinetic, non-dilated, fibrotic or fibrofatty left ventricular myocardium and ventricular arrhythmias with a right bundle branch block pattern, with limited to no involvement of the right ventricle. This condition is also precisely known by its exact synonyms: ALVC, left ventricular ACM, and left-dominant arrhythmogenic cardiomyopathy.

Arrhythmogenic biventricular cardiomyopathy is a type of intrinsic cardiomyopathy characterized by hypokinetic, non-dilated, fibrotic or fibrofatty replacement in both the left and right ventricular myocardium. This condition is associated with ventricular arrhythmias with left and right bundle branch block patterns. Furthermore, arrhythmogenic biventricular cardiomyopathy is also known by its exact synonym, biventricular ACM.

The neurodevelopmental disorder with hypotonia, language delay, and skeletal defects, with or without seizures, is a type of autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder and also falls under something that inherently has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is precisely defined as an autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder characterized by a spectrum of behavioral abnormalities and developmental delays. These range from mild-to-moderate impaired intellectual development with expressive language delay, to severely impaired intellectual development, severe hypotonia leading to delayed walking or an inability to walk, and poor or absent speech. The disorder has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the CACNA1C gene located on chromosome 12p13.33. This disorder is exactly synonymous with NEDHLSS and has an exact match in the OMIM database with the identifier OMIM:620029.

Spastic tetraplegia, thin corpus callosum, and progressive microcephaly is a type of autosomal recessive intellectual developmental disorder. It is characterized by neonatal or infantile onset of spastic tetraplegia, thin corpus callosum, progressive microcephaly, and severely impaired global development. This disorder has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the SLC1A4 gene on chromosome 2p14. It is also known by its exact synonym SPATCCM. Furthermore, it is matched exactly to several databases: GARD:13425, OMIM:616657, ORDO:447997, and UMLS_CUI:C4225254.

The Syndromic X-linked Intellectual Developmental Disorder Bain Type is a kind of Syndromic X-linked Intellectual Disability characterized by delayed psychomotor development, impaired intellectual development with behavioral abnormalities, and musculoskeletal and growth abnormalities. This condition is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the HNRNPH2 gene on chromosome Xq22.1. It is also known by several exact synonyms: HNRNPH2-RNDD, HNRNPH2-related neurodevelopmental disorder, MRXSB, and Mental Retardation, X-linked, Syndrome, Bain Type. Furthermore, this disorder is precisely matched with the following identifiers: GARD:13442, NCI:C183311, OMIM:300986, and UMLS_CUI:C4310814.

Muscular disease is the same as a disease that intersects with at least one disease having a location in some muscle tissue. It is a type of musculoskeletal system disease, with a definition stating that a muscular disease is a musculoskeletal system disease that affects the muscles.

Bone disease is the same as something that is an intersection of something that is a disease and something that has a location in some bone element. Additionally, bone disease is a type of connective tissue disease. It is defined as a connective tissue disease that affects the structure or development of bone or causes an impairment of normal bone function. Moreover, bone disease has a related synonym, skeletal disease.
Bone remodeling disease is a type of bone disease characterized by abnormalities in formation or resorption that occur within the bone.
Bone development disease is a type of bone disease, characterized by a condition that results in abnormal growth and development. This condition is found in bone or cartilage.

Bone deterioration disease is a type of bone structure disease and is also a type of condition that is located in some bone element. It is defined as a bone structure disease that results in a change or damage of structure located in the bone.
Ischemic bone disease is a type of bone disease defined as a bone disease that results in an interruption of the blood supply located in the bone.

An X-linked dominant disease is both a type of X-linked monogenic disease and is defined as an X-linked monogenic disease that has its material basis in dominant inheritance. It is also equivalent to an intersection involving a disease and something that at least has its material basis in some X-linked dominant inheritance.

Bone structure disease is a type of bone disease and is also recognized as a type of condition characterized by having a phenotype of abnormal bone structure. It is defined as a bone disease that arises from an abnormality in the location or function of the skeletal structure.
Bone resorption disease is a type of bone remodeling disease, defined as a bone remodeling disease that results in an abnormal decrease of bone density or mass.

An X-linked recessive disease is the same as something that is both a disease and has at least a material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance. This disease is a type of X-linked monogenic disease. Furthermore, an X-linked recessive disease is defined as an X-linked monogenic disease that has its material basis in recessive inheritance.

A chromosomal disease is the same as a condition that is both a disease and has, at a minimum, a material basis in variations of chromosome structure. It is a subtype of genetic disease. Specifically, a chromosomal disease is defined as a genetic disease that has its material basis in extra, missing, or re-arranged chromosomes.

Physical disorder is the same as an intersection of a disease and something that at least has its basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. Moreover, a physical disorder is a type of disease and is defined as a disease that has its material basis in a genetic abnormality, error with embryonic development, infection, or compromised intrauterine environment. Additionally, physical disorder is exactly synonymous with congenital disorder.

Spina bifida is a type of neural tube defect and is characterized by the incomplete closing of the spine and membranes around the spinal cord during early development. It has exact matches with MESH:D016135 and NCI:C101214.

Dysbaric osteonecrosis is a type of ischemic bone disease, which is defined as an ischemic bone disease that has a material basis in nitrogen embolization located in bone. It also has exact synonyms, including Caisson disease of bone and DON.

Metaphyseal dysplasia, a type of osteochondrodysplasia, is characterized by abnormally broad ends of the arm and leg long bones, resembling a boat oar or paddle due to enlargement of the spongy inner layer of bone. It is also known by exact synonyms such as Bakwin-Krida syndrome, Pyle's disease, and Pyle-Cohn syndrome.

Jansen's metaphyseal chondrodysplasia, also known exactly as Jansen Disease, Jansen Metaphyseal Dysostosis, Jansen metaphyseal chondrodysplasia, and Murk Jansen Type Metaphyseal Chondrodysplasia, is a type of autosomal dominant disease, metaphyseal dysplasia, and is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and a phenotype of disproportionate short limb short stature. It is defined as a metaphyseal dysplasia that results from a mutation in the PTH receptor, leading to short-limbed dwarfism.

Schmid metaphyseal chondrodysplasia is a type of metaphyseal dysplasia that has a phenotype characterized by severe short stature. It is defined as a metaphyseal dysplasia that results in dwarfism and bowed legs. Additionally, Schmid metaphyseal chondrodysplasia is exactly synonymous with Japanese type spondylometaphyseal dysplasia and Schmid type metaphyseal dysplasia.

Otospodylomegaepiphyseal dysplasia autosomal recessive is a disorder characterized by several key features. It is categorized as an autosomal recessive disease, fitting within the broader classification of osteochondrodysplasias. This condition is fundamentally linked to autosomal recessive inheritance, indicating that it arises due to mutations in both copies of a specific gene in an individual. It is associated with certain phenotypes, including platyspondyly, and has a particular predilection for affecting the epiphysis, the end part of long bones. Specifically, it is caused by autosomal recessive inheritance of mutations in the COL11A2 gene, leading to notable symptoms such as enlargement of epiphyses in hands and feet, distinct facial features, platyspondyly, and hearing loss. Additionally, otospondylomegaepiphyseal dysplasia autosomal recessive is known by several exact synonyms, including CHONDRODYSTROPHY WITH SENSORINEURAL DEAFNESS, NANCE-INSLEY SYNDROME, NANCE-SWEENEY CHONDRODYSPLASIA, and OSMEDB.

Spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia is a type of spinal disease and also falls under the category of osteochondrodysplasia. This condition is characterized as a type of disease that affects specific locations, including the vertebral column, epiphysis, and metaphysis. Moreover, spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia is defined as an osteochondrodysplasia that leads to abnormalities of bone growth in the vertebral column, epiphysis, and metaphysis.

Spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia Strudwick type is a specific form of spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia and an autosomal dominant disease, indicating its genetic inheritance pattern is autosomal dominant. It has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance and is characterized by several phenotypes including pectus carinatum, platyspondyly, talipes equinovarus, coxa vara, and hyperlordosis. Additionally, it exhibits symptoms such as short stature and has its disease location primarily in the vertebral column. The definition of spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia Strudwick type encompasses a condition that arises from mutations in the COL2A1 gene, leading to short stature alongside multiple skeletal abnormalities like lordosis, scoliosis, flattened vertebrae, pectus carinatum, coxa vara, clubfoot, and abnormal epiphyses or metaphyses.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 16 is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia and has an exact synonym, SCAR16. It is defined as an autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia characterized by truncal and limb ataxia resulting in gait instability. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the STUB1 gene on chromosome 16p13.

Spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia Missouri type is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia. It is characterized by a basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and exhibits phenotypes including genu varum and pear-shaped vertebrae. Additionally, this condition is associated with the vertebral column. Spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia Missouri type is defined as a spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia that arises from mutations in the MMP13 gene, leading to pear-shaped vertebrae, abnormal metaphyseal changes, and genu varum deformities.
Fibrous dysplasia is a type of bone remodeling disease characterized by the destruction of normal bone and its replacement with fibrous bone tissue.

Craniodiaphyseal dysplasia is a type of osteosclerosis and can be classified as a condition that exhibits a phenotype with increased bone mineral density. It is defined as an osteosclerosis that results in an increased calcium concentration located in the skull, which decreases the size of the cranium foramina and cervical spinal canal. Additionally, craniodiaphyseal dysplasia has an exact match with MESH:C562940.

Craniometaphyseal dysplasia is a type of osteosclerosis and also falls under the category of conditions that exhibit an increased bone mineral density phenotype. It is defined as an osteosclerosis characterized by hyperostosis and sclerosis of the craniofacial bones, accompanied by abnormal modeling of the metaphyses.

SOST-related sclerosing bone dysplasia, also known as van Buchem disease, is a type of autosomal recessive disease characterized by hyperostosis. This condition stems from a mutation in the SOST gene, which leads to the overgrowth of endosteal bone, resulting in dense and wide bones throughout the body, especially in the skull. This disease is also associated with traits such as having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and exhibiting a phenotype of overgrowth.

Worth syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease that is also classified as a type of hyperostosis. It is characterized by having a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance and manifests a phenotype of increased bone mineral density. The condition is defined as a hyperostosis that results from a mutation in the LRP5 gene, leading to increased bone density and bony structures located in the palate. Worth syndrome is also known by several exact synonyms, including Worth's syndrome, autosomal dominant endosteal hyperostosis, autosomal dominant osteosclerosis, and the benign form of Worth hyperostosis corticalis generalisata with torus platinus.

Pycnodysostosis is a type of autosomal recessive disease and osteochondrodysplasia, which is characterized by having at least a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance and a phenotype that includes severe short stature. It is defined as an osteochondrodysplasia that has its material basis in a mutation in the CTSK gene, resulting in dwarfism, brittle bones, osteopetrosis, and shortening of the distal phalanges.

Axial osteomalacia is a type of osteosclerosis and also falls under the category of conditions that exhibit an increased bone mineral density phenotype. Furthermore, it is defined as an osteosclerosis characterized by a resulting coarsening located in trabecular bone.

Fibrogenesis imperfecta ossium is a type of syndrome that is defined as a syndrome involving the abnormality of collagen synthesis in lamellar bones, with manifestations limited to the skeleton. The initial symptom of this condition is frequently spontaneous fractures. Additionally, fibrogenesis imperfecta ossium is exactly synonymous with Baker's disease.

Hypochondroplasia is a type of autosomal dominant disease and osteochondrodysplasia, which is something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as an osteochondrodysplasia that has a material basis in mutation in the FGFR3 gene, affecting the ossification of cartilage and resulting in short limb dwarfism.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 18 is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia, which is defined as an autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia characterized by delayed psychomotor development, severely impaired gait due to cerebellar ataxia, ocular movement abnormalities, and intellectual disability. This condition has its material basis in homozygous mutations in the GRID2 gene on chromosome 4q22. Additionally, autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 18 has the exact synonym SCAR18.

Achondrogenesis is a type of osteochondrodysplasia, which is characterized by several phenotypes including a narrow chest and severe short stature. It is defined as an osteochondrodysplasia that has its material basis in deficient endochondral ossification. This deficiency results in dwarfism, a short trunk, short limbs, anascara, a disproportionately large cranium, and a narrow chest, ultimately leading to death in utero or during the early neonatal period.

Hypochondrogenesis is a type of monogenic disease, osteochondrodysplasia, and it is associated with phenotypes such as hydrops fetalis and symptoms like bloating. It has its basis in genetics, specifically involving mutations in the COL2A1 gene, which affects bone growth. This disease primarily affects the vertebral column and the bony pelvis. Moreover, hypochondrogenesis is defined as an osteochondrodysplasia characterized by a mutation in the COL2A1 gene, resulting in a small body, hydrops fetalis, and abnormal ossification located in the vertebral column or pelvis, with an enlarged abdomen as a symptom.

Kniest dysplasia is a type of autosomal dominant disease and osteochondrodysplasia. It is characterized by a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and presents phenotypes such as malar flattening, severe short stature, and disproportionate short trunk short stature. Kniest dysplasia is defined as an osteochondrodysplasia that results from a mutation in the COL2A1 gene, leading to dwarfism characterized by a short trunk and limbs, along with vision and hearing problems. Symptoms of the disease include large joints, wide-set eyes, and a round flat face.
Stickler Syndrome is a type of syndrome characterized by a distinctive facial appearance, eye abnormalities, hearing loss, and joint problems.

Pseudoachondroplasia is a type of autosomal dominant disease and also falls under the category of osteochondrodysplasia. It is defined by its material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, pseudoachondroplasia is an osteochondrodysplasia characterized by mutations in the COMP gene, which lead to short limb dwarfism. Additionally, it is exactly synonymous with SPONDYLOEPIPHYSEAL DYSPLASIA, PSEUDOACHONDROPLASTIC, and pseudoachondroplastic dysplasia.
Acromesomelic dysplasia is a type of osteochondrodysplasia and is defined as an osteochondrodysplasia that is characterized by mesomelia and acromelia, resulting in short limb dwarfism.

Acromesomelic dysplasia Maroteaux type is a form of acromesomelic dysplasia, which is classified as an autosomal recessive disease. This condition is also categorized as a type of spinal disease, indicating its effects on the vertebral column. It is characterized by a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance and has its disease locations in the vertebral column and limbs. Acromesomelic dysplasia Maroteaux type is defined by an acromesomelic dysplasia that results from a mutation in the NPR-B receptor, leading to severe dwarfism, abnormalities in the vertebral column, and shortening of the middle and distal segments of the limbs. Additionally, acromesomelic dysplasia Maroteaux type is precisely synonymous with acromesomelic dysplasia-1.

Acromesomelic dysplasia Hunter Thompson type is a specific form of autosomal recessive disease and is categorized under acromesomelic dysplasia. It is characterized by a type of condition that inherently has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. This condition is defined by an acromesomelic dysplasia that arises from a mutation in the AMDH gene, leading to a normal axial skeleton but results in fused bones in the hands or feet. Additionally, acromesomelic dysplasia Hunter Thompson type is precisely known as acromesomelic dwarfism and acromesomelic dysplasia-2C.

Acromesomelic dysplasia Grebe type is classified as a type of acromesomelic dysplasia and an autosomal recessive disease, which is a category of disorders that at least have a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is precisely defined as an acromesomelic dysplasia that results from a mutation in CDMP-1, leading to micromelia, the absence of middle and proximal phalanges, and some metacarpal and metatarsal bones. Moreover, "acromesomelic dysplasia-2A" and "grebe chondrodysplasia" are acknowledged as exact synonyms for acromesomelic dysplasia Grebe type.

Albright's Hereditary Osteodystrophy (AHO) is a type of pseudohypoparathyroidism and is also known as pseudohypoparathyroidism type 1a and has the exact synonym Albright Hereditary Osteodystrophy. It is characterized by a specific condition that at least has symptoms including short stature. AHO is defined as a pseudohypoparathyroidism that has its material basis in a lack of responsiveness to parathyroid hormone, which results in the shortening and widening of the long bones located in the hands or feet, along with short stature, obesity, and a rounded face.

Achondrogenesis type IA is a type of achondrogenesis known as achondrogenesis Houston-Harris type. This condition is characterized as an autosomal recessive disease and falls under the category of spinal diseases. It is defined by an abnormal ossification process occurring within the vertebral column or spine. Additionally, achondrogenesis type IA is associated with diseases that manifest in the vertebral column and is linked to conditions that have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance.

Achondrogenesis type IB is a type of achondrogenesis and an autosomal recessive disease, which falls under the broader category of conditions that have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is specifically defined as an achondrogenesis that arises from a mutation in the SLC26A2 gene, leading to clinical manifestations such as umbilical or inguinal hernia and a prominent rounded abdomen. Additionally, achondrogenesis type IB is exactly synonymous with achondrogenesis Fraccaro type.

Achondrogenesis type II is a type of autosomal dominant disease and also a type of achondrogenesis. It is characterized by a condition that has its material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and affects the vertebral column and bony pelvis. Specifically, achondrogenesis type II is defined as a form of achondrogenesis that results from mutations in the COL2A1 gene, leading to symptoms such as underdeveloped lungs, hydrops fetalis, a prominent forehead, and abnormal ossification of the vertebral column or pelvis.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 15 is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia, which is defined as an autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia that has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the RUBCN gene on chromosome 3q29. It also has the exact synonym SCAR15.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 14 is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia, which is also exactly synonymous with SCAR14. It is defined as an autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia characterized by delayed psychomotor development, severe early-onset gait ataxia, eye movement abnormalities, cerebellar atrophy on brain imaging, and intellectual disability. This condition has a material basis in homozygous mutation in the SPTBN2 gene on chromosome 11q13.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 7 (SCAR7) is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia. It is defined as an autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia characterized by the onset of progressive gait difficulties, eye movement abnormalities, and dysarthria in the first or second decade of life. This condition has its material basis in compound heterozygous mutation in the TPP1 gene on chromosome 11p15.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 12 is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia, which is also exactly known as SCAR12. It is defined as an autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia characterized by the onset of generalized seizures in infancy, delayed psychomotor development with mental retardation, and cerebellar ataxia. This condition has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the WWOX gene located on chromosome 16q23.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 2 (SCAR2) is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia. It is defined as an autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia characterized by juvenile onset of progressive cerebellar ataxia, axonal sensorimotor peripheral neuropathy, and increased serum alpha-fetoprotein. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the senataxin gene on chromosome 9q34.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 13 is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia, which is defined as an autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia characterized by delayed psychomotor development beginning in infancy. This condition has its material basis in homozygous mutation in the GRM1 gene on chromosome 6q24. Moreover, autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 13 has the exact synonym SCAR13.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 11 is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia, which is defined as an autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia that has its material basis in homozygous mutation in the SYT14 gene on chromosome 1q32. Additionally, autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 11 has the exact synonym SCAR11.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 17 is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia, which is precisely defined as an autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia that has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the CWF19L1 gene on chromosome 10q24. Furthermore, autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 17 is exactly synonymous with SCAR17.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 19 is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia, which is defined as an autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia characterized by postnatal onset of severe progressive sensorineural hearing loss and progressive cerebellar ataxia. This condition has its material basis in homozygous mutation in the SLC9A1 gene located on chromosome 1p36. Additionally, autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 19 is exactly synonymous with Lichtenstein-Knorr syndrome and SCAR19.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 20 is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia, which is defined as an autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia characterized by severely delayed psychomotor development, poor or absent speech, a wide-based or absent gait, coarse facies, and cerebellar atrophy. This condition has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the SNX14 gene located on chromosome 6q14. Additionally, it is exactly synonymous with SCAR20.

Charcot Marie Tooth disease type 5 is a type of Charcot Marie Tooth disease and an autosomal dominant disease. It is classified as something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. This disease is defined as a Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease characterized by pyramidal features, including extensor plantar responses, a mild increase in tone, and preserved or increased reflexes, but without a spastic gait. Moreover, it has the exact synonym 'hereditary motor and sensory neuropathy with pyramidal features'.
