Charcot Marie Tooth disease type 6 is a type of Charcot Marie Tooth disease, which is defined as a Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease characterized by early-onset optic atrophy resulting in progressive visual loss and peripheral axonal sensorimotor neuropathy with highly variable age at onset and severity. Additionally, it has the exact synonym hereditary motor and sensory neuropathy type 6.
Charcot Marie Tooth disease type 7 is a type of Charcot Marie Tooth disease and is defined as a Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease that is characterized by optic atrophy followed by retinitis pigmentosa.

Mucolipidosis II alpha beta is a type of mucolipidosis that is defined by its characteristics which include short stature, skeletal abnormalities, cardiomegaly, and developmental delay. This is due to a defect in proper lysosomal enzyme phosphorylation and localization, leading to the accumulation of lysosomal substrates. The condition is caused by either homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the GNPTAB gene. It is also precisely known by several synonyms: I-cell disease, inclusion-cell disease, and mucolipidosis II.

Mucolipidosis III alpha/beta is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a subtype of mucolipidosis, characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined by a mutation in the gene that encodes the alpha/beta-subunits precursor gene of GLcNAc-phosphotransferase. Mucolipidosis III alpha/beta is also exactly synonymous with mucolipidosis III and pseudo-Hurler polydystrophy.

Intestinal pseudo obstruction is a type of colonic disease characterized by a bowel obstruction resulting from the impairment of the muscle contractions that move food through the digestive tract. It is also exactly referred to as Chronic intestinal pseudo-obstruction and neuronal intestinal dysplasia.
Spina bifida occulta is a type of spina bifida that is defined by minor splits in the vertebrae, characterized by the outer part of some of the vertebrae not being completely closed.
A neural tube defect is a type of physical disorder characterized by incomplete closure of the neural tube.

Neu Laxova syndrome 2 is a type of serine deficiency and is also a type of condition that at least has the symptom of some ptosis. It is defined as a serine deficiency characterized by multiple fatal malformations including ichthyosis, microcephaly, central nervous system abnormalities, limb deformities, intrauterine growth restriction, proptosis, anasarca, and micrognathia. This condition has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance of a mutation in the PSAT1 gene on chromosome 9q21.1, which causes issues in producing the amino acid serine.

Neu Laxova syndrome 1 is a type of serine deficiency and also a type of condition that at least has ptosis as a symptom. It is defined as a serine deficiency characterized by multiple fatal malformations including ichthyosis, microcephaly, central nervous system abnormalities, limb deformities, intrauterine growth restriction, proptosis, anasarca, and micrognathia. This condition has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance of a mutation in the PHGDH gene on chromosome 1p12, which causes issues in producing the amino acid serine.

Hypophosphatemic nephrolithiasis osteoporosis 1 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of hypophosphatemic nephrolithiasis osteoporosis. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally arises from autosomal dominant inheritance. This condition is defined as a hypophosphatemic nephrolithiasis/osteoporosis that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the SLC34A1 gene on chromosome 5q35.

Hypophosphatemic nephrolithiasis osteoporosis 2 is a specific type of both autosomal dominant disease and hypophosphatemic nephrolithiasis osteoporosis. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally arises from autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, it is defined as a hypophosphatemic nephrolithiasis/osteoporosis condition that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the SLC9A3R1 gene located on chromosome 17q25.1.

Nonsyndromic congenital nail disorder 1 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of nonsyndromic congenital nail disorder. It is characterized by a condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance and also has a basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. Nonsyndromic congenital nail disorder 1 is defined as a nonsyndromic congenital nail disorder characterized by excessive longitudinal striations and numerous superficial pits on the nails, which have a distinctive rough, sandpaper-like appearance. It has exact synonyms, including nonsyndromic congenital nail disorder 10 and twenty-nail dystrophy.

Nonsyndromic congenital nail disorder 2 is a type of disease that falls under several categories: it is an autosomal dominant disease, a nonsyndromic congenital nail disorder, and it has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Furthermore, it is associated with abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. It is defined as a nonsyndromic congenital nail disorder characterized by nails that are abnormally thin and concave from side to side, with turned up edges.

Nonsyndromic congenital nail disorder 3 is categorized as a type of autosomal dominant disease and also as a type of autosomal recessive disease. It falls under the broader category of nonsyndromic congenital nail disorders. This disorder is described as having a material basis in both autosomal dominant and autosomal recessive inheritance patterns. Additionally, it is linked to abnormalities in prenatal development or birth. Nonsyndromic congenital nail disorder 3 is defined by its characteristic feature, which is the white discoloration of the nails.

Nonsyndromic congenital nail disorder 4 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a nonsyndromic congenital nail disorder that has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is also linked to abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. It is defined as a nonsyndromic congenital nail disorder characterized by the complete absence or severe hypoplasia of all fingernails and toenails without significant bone anomalies. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the R-spondin-4 gene on chromosome 20p13. Furthermore, nonsyndromic congenital nail disorder 4 is exactly synonymous with Hyponychia Congenita and Anonychia Congenita.

Nonsyndromic congenital nail disorder 5 is a type of nonsyndromic congenital nail disorder, which is an autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by a decreased growth rate, thick and hard nails, and a straight or concave proximal edge of detachment. This disorder has its material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance and is associated with abnormalities of prenatal development or birth.

Nonsyndromic congenital nail disorder 6 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a subtype of nonsyndromic congenital nail disorder. It is characterized by partial absences of nails, indicating its basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. This disorder's material basis lies in autosomal dominant inheritance.

Nonsyndromic congenital nail disorder 7 is characterized by a type of autosomal dominant disease and falls under the category of nonsyndromic congenital nail disorders. It is specifically associated with a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and has its origins in abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. The disorder is defined by nails that exhibit longitudinal streaks, thinning of the nail plate, poorly developed or absent lunulae, and disturbed formation of the nail plate, which increases the vulnerability of the free nail margins.

Nonsyndromic congenital nail disorder 8 is classified as a type of autosomal dominant disease and is also recognized as a type of nonsyndromic congenital nail disorder. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and is associated with abnormalities in prenatal development or birth. Additionally, this disorder is located at the intersection of the nail and foot, specifically impacting the toenails. It is defined as a nonsyndromic congenital nail disorder characterized by dystrophy of the toenails only and is exactly synonymous with isolated toenail dystrophy.

Nonsyndromic congenital nail disorder 9 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a subtype of nonsyndromic congenital nail disorders. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is associated with some abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. Additionally, it is defined as a nonsyndromic congenital nail disorder where individuals have normal nails at birth, but dystrophic changes occur within the first decade of life, leading to onycholysis of the fingernails and anonychia of the toenails.

Tubular Aggregate Myopathy 1 is a type of myopathy and an autosomal dominant disease, which is categorized by a specific type of inheritance that at least has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a myopathy characterized by the presence of tubular aggregates in myofibrils, and its material basis is in a heterozygous mutation in the STIM1 gene on chromosome 11p15. Additionally, Tubular Aggregate Myopathy 1 has a narrower match, ORDO:2593.

Reducing body myopathy 1a is a type of myopathy and an X-linked dominant disease that at least has a material basis in some X-linked dominant inheritance. It is defined as a myopathy characterized by the presence of intracytoplasmic inclusion bodies strongly stained by menadione-linked alpha-glycerophosphate dehydrogenase in the absence of substrate, alpha-glycerophosphate, with infantile or early childhood onset. This condition has its material basis in mutations in the FHL1 gene on chromosome Xq26.

Myofibrillar myopathy 1 is classified as a type of myofibrillar myopathy and is also recognized as an autosomal dominant disease as well as an autosomal recessive disease. It fundamentally has a material basis in both autosomal dominant and autosomal recessive inheritance patterns. This condition is defined as a myofibrillar myopathy that arises from heterozygous, homozygous, or compound heterozygous mutations in the desmin gene located on chromosome 2q35. Additionally, myofibrillar myopathy 1 is precisely synonymous with autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophy type 2R and desminopathy.

Myofibrillar myopathy 2 is a type of myofibrillar myopathy and an autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized as something that has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, myofibrillar myopathy 2 is defined as a myofibrillar myopathy that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the alpha-B-crystallin gene located on chromosome 11q23. It is also exactly synonymous with alpha-B crystallinopathy.

Myofibrillar myopathy 3 is a type of autosomal dominant disease, which is a specific kind of myofibrillar myopathy. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. This condition is defined by a myofibrillar myopathy that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the MYOT gene located on chromosome 5q31. Myofibrillar myopathy 3 is also known by several exact synonyms, including LGMD 1A, autosomal dominant limb-girdle muscular dystrophy type 1A, myotilinopathy, and spheroid body myopathy.

Myofibrillar myopathy 4, also known exactly as zaspopathy, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of myofibrillar myopathy. It is categorized as something that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. The definition of myofibrillar myopathy 4 is a myofibrillar myopathy that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the ZASP gene on chromosome 10.

Myofibrillar myopathy 5 is a type of myofibrillar myopathy and an autosomal dominant disease. It is also classified under conditions that have a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, myofibrillar myopathy 5 is defined as a myofibrillar myopathy that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the FLNC gene on chromosome 7q32. Additionally, it is exactly synonymous with filaminopathy.

Myofibrillar myopathy 6 is a type of myofibrillar myopathy and an autosomal dominant disease that is characterized by a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, it is defined as a myofibrillar myopathy that has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the BAG3 gene on chromosome 10q26. Additionally, it is also known by the related synonym BAG3-related myofibrillar myopathy.

Myofibrillar myopathy 7 is a type of myofibrillar myopathy and an autosomal recessive disease. It is defined as a myofibrillar myopathy that has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the KY gene on chromosome 3q22. This condition is also categorized as something that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Myopathy lactic acidosis and sideroblastic anemia is a type of mitochondrial myopathy. It is defined as a mitochondrial myopathy characterized by progressive exercise intolerance manifesting in childhood, the onset of sideroblastic anemia around adolescence, lactic acidemia, and mitochondrial myopathy.

Compton North Congenital Myopathy is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which is also a physical disorder and a form of congenital myopathy. It is defined by its material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance and is characterized by symptoms such as muscle weakness. Moreover, the disease's basis is found in some abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. It is precisely defined as a congenital myopathy that has its material basis in homozygous mutations in the CNTN1 gene on chromosome 12q12. This condition is characterized, antenatally, by fetal akinesia, intrauterine growth restriction, and polyhydramnios, and following birth, by severe neonatal hypotonia, severe generalized skeletal, bulbar, and respiratory muscle weakness, multiple flexion contractures, and normal creatine kinase serum levels. Compton North Congenital Myopathy is also exactly synonymous with Congenital Myopathy 12.

Congenital myopathy 4a, also known by its exact synonyms CFTD and congenital fiber-type disproportion, is a type of autosomal dominant disease, physical disorder, and congenital myopathy. It is associated with autosomal dominant inheritance and is based on some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. This condition is defined as a congenital myopathy characterized by skeletal muscle weakness, particularly in the muscles of the shoulders, upper arms, hips, and thighs.

Cylindrical spirals myopathy is a type of congenital myopathy and is also a type of condition that, at a minimum, manifests symptoms of muscle weakness. It is defined as a congenital myopathy characterized by global muscle weakness, hypotonia, myotonia, and cramps, accompanied by cylindrical, spiral-shaped inclusions.

Microcephaly and chorioretinopathy 1 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, syndrome, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome that is characterized by delayed psychomotor development and visual impairment, often accompanied by short stature, and has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TUBGCP6 gene.

Microcephaly and chorioretinopathy 2 is a syndrome that is not only classified as an autosomal recessive disease but also as a condition that fundamentally arises from autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined by a collection of symptoms including delayed psychomotor development, visual impairment, and short stature, which are attributed to homozygous mutations in the PLK4 gene.

Microcephaly and chorioretinopathy 3 is a syndrome that is also a type of autosomal recessive disease, and it is something that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by congenital microcephaly and chorioretinal dysplasia associated with poor vision and nystagmus, and it has its material basis in compound heterozygous mutation in the TUBGCP4 gene.
Myoglobinuria is a type of myopathy and is defined as a myopathy characterized by an increased urinary excretion of myoglobin.

Infantile myofibromatosis is a type of connective tissue benign neoplasm, which is defined as a connective tissue benign neoplasm characterized by the development of benign tumors in the skin, striated muscles, bones, and, in exceptional cases, visceral organs. It is also exactly synonymous with lipofibromatosis.

Contractures pterygia and spondylocarpotarsal fusion syndrome is a type of monogenic disease, which means it has a basis in a single gene, and it is also recognized as a syndrome. It is characterized by a syndrome that involves permanently bent fingers, short stature, rocker-bottom or club feet, joints that are bent in a fixed position, union or webbing of the skin between the fingers, and/or webbing of the neck, inside bend of the elbows, back of the knees, and armpits. Additionally, this syndrome has an exact synonym, which is multiple pterygium syndrome.

Mitochondrial complex III deficiency nuclear type 1 is a type of mitochondrial complex III deficiency and also falls under the category of conditions that have their basis in some structural variant. It is defined as a mitochondrial complex III deficiency characterized by onset at birth of lactic acidosis, hypotonia, hypoglycemia, failure to thrive, encephalopathy, and delayed psychomotor development. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the nuclear-encoded BCS1L gene on chromosome 2q35.

Mitochondrial complex III deficiency nuclear type 3 is a specific type of mitochondrial complex III deficiency and is categorized under diseases that have their basis in some structural variant. It is defined as a mitochondrial complex III deficiency that has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the UQCRB gene located on chromosome 8q22.

Mitochondrial complex III deficiency nuclear type 4 is categorized as a type of mitochondrial complex III deficiency and also falls into a broader category of conditions that have their basis in some structural variant. Specifically, this condition is defined by a mitochondrial complex III deficiency that originates from a homozygous mutation in the UQCRQ gene located on chromosome 5q31.

Mitochondrial complex III deficiency nuclear type 5 is a form of mitochondrial complex III deficiency, which falls under the category of diseases that have their basis in some structural variant. It is specifically defined as a mitochondrial complex III deficiency marked by a neonatal onset of severe metabolic acidosis, accompanied by hyperammonemia and hypoglycemia, and has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the UQCRC2 gene located on chromosome 16p12.

Mitochondrial complex III deficiency nuclear type 6 is a type of mitochondrial complex III deficiency and also a type of condition that has its basis in some structural variant. It is defined as a mitochondrial complex III deficiency characterized by onset in early childhood of episodic acute lactic acidosis, ketoacidosis, and insulin-responsive hyperglycemia, usually associated with infection. This condition has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the CYC1 gene located on chromosome 8q24.

Mitochondrial complex III deficiency nuclear type 7 is a type of mitochondrial complex III deficiency and is also a type of condition that at least has its basis in some structural variant. It is defined as a mitochondrial complex III deficiency that has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the UQCC2 gene on chromosome 6p21.

Mitochondrial complex III deficiency nuclear type 8 is a type of mitochondrial complex III deficiency and is also a type of condition with a basis in a structural variant. It is defined as a mitochondrial complex III deficiency characterized by childhood onset of progressive neurodegeneration that has a material basis in a homozygous mutation in the LYRM7 gene on chromosome 5q23.

Mitochondrial complex III deficiency nuclear type 9 is a specific form of mitochondrial complex III deficiency, which belongs to a category of diseases that have their basis in some structural variant. It is defined as a mitochondrial complex III deficiency that has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the UQCC3 gene located on chromosome 11q12.

Mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 1 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome that is characterized by various symptoms and conditions. It is specifically identified as having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is known to cause symptoms such as ptosis. The syndrome is defined by its onset between the second and fifth decades of life, which includes ptosis, progressive external ophthalmoplegia, gastrointestinal dysmotility, cachexia, diffuse leukoencephalopathy, peripheral neuropathy, and mitochondrial dysfunction. The disease originates from either homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the nuclear-encoded thymidine phosphorylase gene located on chromosome 22q13. Additionally, mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 1 is precisely referred to as mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 1 (MNGIE type) and mitochondrial neurogastrointestinal encephalopathy syndrome, TYMP-related, serving as its exact synonyms.

Mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 2 (MDDS2) is classified as a type of autosomal recessive disease and falls under the broader category of mitochondrial DNA depletion syndromes. It is characterized by a specific set of criteria, including childhood onset of muscle weakness associated with depletion of mtDNA in skeletal muscle. The underlying cause of MDDS2 is the autosomal recessive inheritance of homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the mitochondrial thymidine kinase gene located on chromosome 16q21. Additionally, MDDS2 can be referred to by its exact synonym, TK2-related mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome, myopathic form. This syndrome manifests symptoms such as muscle weakness and is inherently linked to autosomal recessive inheritance patterns.

Mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 3 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome, which inherently has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. This syndrome is distinguished by its onset in infancy, featuring progressive liver failure, neurologic abnormalities, hypoglycemia, and increased lactate levels in body fluids. The condition arises from autosomal recessive inheritance, specifically due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the deoxyguanosine kinase gene located on chromosome 2p13. Additionally, mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 3 is also precisely known as deoxyguanosine kinase deficiency.

Alpers Huttenlocher Syndrome is a type of autosomal recessive disease and is also classified as a mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome. It shares the characteristic of having a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. The syndrome is defined as a mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome characterized by a clinical triad of psychomotor retardation, intractable epilepsy, and liver failure in infants and young children. This condition has its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance of homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the nuclear gene encoding mitochondrial DNA polymerase gamma on chromosome 15q26.

Alpers Huttenlocher Syndrome is known by several exact synonyms including Alper's Syndrome, Alpers Disease, Alpers Progressive Infantile Poliodystrophy, Alpers Syndrome, Alpers' Disease or Gray-Matter Degeneration, Diffuse Cerebral Sclerosis of Schilder, Mitochondrial DNA Depletion Syndrome 4A, and Progressive Sclerosing Poliodystrophy. Additionally, Alpers Huttenlocher Syndrome has an exact match with the MESH identifier D002549.

Mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 4B, which is also known exactly as mitochondrial neurogastrointestinal encephalopathy syndrome, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and is one of the mitochondrial DNA depletion syndromes. This syndrome is characterized by conditions that have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance, including chronic gastrointestinal dysmotility and pseudoobstruction, cachexia, progressive external ophthalmoplegia, axonal sensory ataxic neuropathy, and muscle weakness. Specifically, its material basis is linked to the autosomal recessive inheritance of compound heterozygous mutation in the mitochondrial DNA polymerase gamma gene on chromosome 15q26. Additionally, one of the symptoms of this syndrome is muscle weakness.

Mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 5 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which is also a specific form of mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome. It is defined by a condition that includes infantile onset of hypotonia, progressive neurologic deterioration, a hyperkinetic-dystonic movement disorder, external ophthalmoplegia, deafness, and variable renal tubular dysfunction. This syndrome has its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance, particularly through homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the beta subunit of the succinate-CoA ligase gene located on chromosome 13q14. Additionally, mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 5 is exactly synonymous with succinate-CoA ligase deficiency.

Mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 6 (MDDS6) is a specific type of autosomal recessive disease and is one of the mitochondrial DNA depletion syndromes. It is characterized by a condition that inherently has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. More precisely, MDDS6 is defined by the infantile onset of progressive liver failure, often leading to death within the first year of life. This condition results from autosomal recessive inheritance of homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the mitochondrial inner membrane protein MPV17 gene located on chromosome 2p23. Furthermore, MDDS6 is also known by its exact synonyms, MPV17-related hepatocerebral mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome and Navajo neurohepatopathy.

Mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 7 (MDDS7) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome, indicating that it has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. MDDS7 is characterized by progressive ataxia, hypotonia, hyporeflexia, athetosis, and sensory impairment. This syndrome is caused by autosomal recessive homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the C10ORF2 gene, which encodes the twinkle and twinky proteins, on chromosome 10q24. Additionally, MDDS7 is also known by the exact synonyms OHAHA syndrome and infantile-onset spinocerebellar ataxia.

Mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 8A is a type of autosomal recessive disease and also falls under the broader category of mitochondrial DNA depletion syndromes. It is characterized by a condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, this syndrome is defined as a mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome characterized by neonatal hypotonia, lactic acidosis, and neurologic deterioration. It has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance of homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ribonucleotide reductase regulatory TP53 inducible subunit M2B gene on chromosome 8q22. Additionally, mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 8A has an exact synonym: RRM2B-related mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome, encephalomyopathic form with renal tubulopathy.

Mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 9 (MDDS9) is a form of autosomal recessive disease and a specific type of mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome, which distinctly has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. This syndrome is characterized by an infantile onset of hypotonia, lactic acidosis, severe psychomotor retardation, progressive neurologic deterioration, and the excretion of methylmalonic acid. This condition arises from autosomal recessive inheritance of homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the alpha subunit of the succinate-CoA ligase gene on chromosome 2p11. Additionally, MDDS9 is exactly synonymous with fatal infantile lactic acidosis, establishing its severity and specific symptoms associated with the condition.

Mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 11 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific variant of mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome that is fundamentally based on autosomal recessive inheritance. This condition is characterized by symptoms such as muscle weakness. More precisely, it is defined as a syndrome that manifests in childhood or adulthood with progressive external ophthalmoplegia (PEO), muscle weakness and atrophy, exercise intolerance, and respiratory insufficiency due to muscle weakness. This is due to autosomal recessive inheritance of homozygous mutation in the mitochondrial genome maintenance exonuclease 1 gene on chromosome 20p11. Additionally, mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 11 is exactly synonymous with progressive external ophthalmoplegia-myopathy-emaciation syndrome.

Mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 12a is a specific type of mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome and also falls under the category of autosomal dominant diseases. It is characterized as a condition that at least partially arises from autosomal dominant inheritance. This syndrome is defined by severe hypotonia due to mitochondrial dysfunction, which is apparent at birth. Its material basis is an autosomal dominant inheritance of a heterozygous mutation in the solute carrier family 25 member 4 gene located on chromosome 4q35.

Mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 13, also precisely known as FBXL4 deficiency, FBXL4-related encephalomyopathic mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome, and mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 13, encephalomyopathic type, is a specific kind of autosomal recessive disease. It belongs to the broader category of mitochondrial DNA depletion syndromes and is notably characterized by being a condition that essentially arises from autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, this syndrome is defined by its early infantile onset of encephalopathy, hypotonia, lactic acidosis, and severe global developmental delay. This condition has its material basis in the autosomal recessive inheritance of homozygous mutations in the F-box and leucine-rich repeat protein 4 gene located on chromosome 6q16.

Sengers syndrome is a type of autosomal recessive disease, mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome characterized by congenital cataracts, hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, skeletal myopathy, exercise intolerance, and lactic acidosis, but with normal mental development. This condition has its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance of homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the acylglycerol kinase gene on chromosome 7q34. Sengers syndrome is also precisely known as mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 10 and mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 10 (cardiomyopathic type).

Multiple mitochondrial dysfunctions syndrome 1 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and also a type of multiple mitochondrial dysfunctions syndrome. It is characterized by a condition that has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance and exhibits symptoms such as muscle weakness. Specifically, this syndrome is defined as a multiple mitochondrial dysfunctions syndrome that manifests through weakness, respiratory failure, lack of neurologic development, lactic acidosis, and early death. This condition has its material basis in the autosomal recessive inheritance of homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the NFU1 iron-sulfur cluster scaffold gene on chromosome 2p13. Furthermore, multiple mitochondrial dysfunctions syndrome 1 has an exact synonym, NFU1 deficiency.

Multiple mitochondrial dysfunctions syndrome 2 is classified as an autosomal recessive disease and falls under the broader category of multiple mitochondrial dysfunctions syndrome. It is characterized by a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, this syndrome is defined by increased serum glycine and lactate, developmental regression in infancy, an encephalopathic disease course that includes seizures, spasticity, loss of head control, and abnormal movement. This is due to an autosomal recessive inheritance of homozygous mutation in the bolA family member 3 gene located on chromosome 2p13. Additionally, multiple mitochondrial dysfunctions syndrome 2 is precisely known as BOLA3 deficiency and also referred to as multiple mitochondrial dysfunctions syndrome 2 with hyperglycinemia.

Multiple mitochondrial dysfunctions syndrome 3 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, and it falls under the broader category of multiple mitochondrial dysfunctions syndrome. This condition is also considered a type of disorder that fundamentally arises from autosomal recessive inheritance. It is specifically defined as a multiple mitochondrial dysfunctions syndrome characterized by the loss of previously acquired developmental milestones within the first months or years of life. This syndrome's material basis is the autosomal recessive inheritance of a homozygous mutation in the iron-sulfur cluster assembly factor IBA57 gene located on chromosome 1q42. Additionally, multiple mitochondrial dysfunctions syndrome 3 is exactly synonymous with IBA57 deficiency.

Multiple mitochondrial dysfunctions syndrome 4 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and falls under the broader category of multiple mitochondrial dysfunctions syndrome. It is described as a condition that initially presents with normal development for the first few months of life, but is followed by a progressive loss of motor and social skills along with hypotonia, spasticity, and nystagmus, ultimately leading to early childhood death. The condition fundamentally arises from autosomal recessive inheritance, specifically due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the iron-sulfur cluster assembly 2 gene located on chromosome 14q24. This elucidates the disease's material basis in a form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Multiple Endocrine Neoplasia Type 4 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and falls under the category of Multiple Endocrine Neoplasia. It is characterized by a condition that has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, Multiple Endocrine Neoplasia Type 4 is defined by hyperparathyroidism and multiple endocrine tumors. This condition arises due to mutations in the CDKN1B gene located on chromosome 12p13, which leads to a reduction in the amount of functional p27 tumor suppressor protein, thereby allowing cells to proliferate unchecked. Additionally, Multiple Endocrine Neoplasia Type 4 is exactly synonymous with Multiple Endocrine Neoplasia, Type IV.

Multiple congenital anomalies hypotonia seizures syndrome 1 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific category of multiple congenital anomalies hypotonia seizures syndrome. It is characterized by a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is also defined by having a foundation in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. The syndrome is defined as a multiple congenital anomalies-hypotonia-seizures syndrome characterized by neonatal hypotonia, lack of psychomotor development, seizures, dysmorphic features, and variable congenital anomalies involving the cardiac, urinary, and gastrointestinal systems. This condition has its material basis in homozygous mutation in the PIGN gene on chromosome 18q21.

Multiple Congenital Anomalies Hypotonia Seizures Syndrome 2 (MCAHS2) is a type of X-linked recessive disease and a form of Multiple Congenital Anomalies Hypotonia Seizures Syndrome. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance and is also based on some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. MCAHS2 is defined as a syndrome characterized by dysmorphic features, neonatal hypotonia, myoclonic seizures, and variable abnormalities involving the central nervous, cardiac, and urinary systems, resulting from a mutation in the PIGA gene located on chromosome Xp22. Additionally, MCAHS2 is precisely known by several synonyms, including Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 20, Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 20, and Glycosylphosphatidylinositol Biosynthesis Defect 4.

Multiple Congenital Anomalies Hypotonia Seizures Syndrome 3 (MCAHS3) is categorized as a type of autosomal recessive disease, which falls under the broader classification of Multiple Congenital Anomalies Hypotonia Seizures Syndrome. It is characterized by conditions that have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and abnormalities rooted in prenatal development or birth. MCAHS3 is specifically identified by neonatal hypotonia, a lack of psychomotor development, seizures, dysmorphic features, and variable congenital anomalies affecting the cardiac, urinary, and gastrointestinal systems. This syndrome is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the PIGT gene located on chromosome 20q13. Additionally, MCAHS3 is also known by the exact synonyms “M Syndrome” and “Light Fixation Seizure Syndrome.”

Mosaic variegated aneuploidy syndrome 1 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and also falls under the broader category of mosaic variegated aneuploidy syndrome. It is defined by its nature of having at least a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, this syndrome is characterized by slow growth both before and after birth, a stature shorter than average, unusually small head size, and an increased risk of cancer in childhood. The condition is rooted in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the BUB1B gene located on chromosome 15q15.

Mosaic variegated aneuploidy syndrome 2 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, and it is also a subtype of mosaic variegated aneuploidy syndrome. This syndrome is characterized by growth that slows before and after birth while typically maintaining a normal head size. Its material basis is in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance, specifically due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CEP57 gene on chromosome 11q21.

Congenital fibrosis of the extraocular muscles is a type of physical disorder, ocular motility disease, and something that has its basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. It is defined as an ocular motility disease characterized by the inability to move the eyes in certain directions, droopy eyelids, and eyes that are fixed in an abnormal position.

Childhood acute lymphocytic leukemia is a type of acute lymphoblastic leukemia and also a type of condition that begins in childhood. It is defined as an acute lymphocytic leukemia occurring during childhood and is exactly synonymous with Childhood Acute Lymphoblastic Leukemia.

Childhood T-cell acute lymphoblastic leukemia (T-ALL) is a type of childhood acute lymphocytic leukemia, T-cell acute lymphoblastic leukemia, and something that at least has a material basis in some T cells. Additionally, its existence starts during some childhood onset. It is defined as a childhood acute lymphoblastic leukemia that has a material basis in T-cells. Furthermore, it has exact synonyms including T-cell childhood acute lymphocytic leukemia and childhood precursor T-lymphoblastic lymphoma/leukemia.

Childhood B cell acute lymphoblastic leukemia is a type of lymphoma and a type of childhood acute lymphocytic leukemia. It is a condition that at least has a material basis in some lymphocyte of B lineage and its existence starts during some childhood onset. Moreover, it is defined as a childhood acute lymphoblastic leukemia that has a material basis in B-cells.

Lymphoblastic lymphoma is a type of lymphoma characterized by a lymphoma that has its material basis in immature malignant lymphocytes (lymphoblasts) committed to the B-cell or T-cell lineage. It is primarily located in lymph nodes or extranodal sites.

T cell childhood lymphoblastic lymphoma is a type of lymphoblastic lymphoma, T cell non-Hodgkin lymphoma, and something that at least has a material basis in some T cells. It is also a type of something whose existence starts during some childhood onset. Moreover, T cell childhood lymphoblastic lymphoma is defined as a lymphoblastic lymphoma that has a material basis in T cells and occurs during childhood. Additionally, it has an exact synonym: Childhood T lymphoblastic lymphoma.

Adult acute monocytic leukemia is a type of acute monocytic leukemia, and it represents a form of leukemia that begins during adult onset. It is defined as an acute monocytic leukemia occurring in adults.
Adrenocorticotropic hormone deficiency is a type of hypopituitarism that is defined by a decreased or absent production of adrenocorticotropic hormone by the pituitary gland.

Medium chain acyl CoA dehydrogenase deficiency is a type of lipid metabolism disorder characterized by a deficiency of the enzyme medium chain acyl-CoA dehydrogenase. This deficiency results in the inability to convert medium chain fatty acids to energy, particularly during fasting.

Short chain acyl CoA dehydrogenase deficiency is a type of lipid metabolism disorder that is defined by a deficiency of the enzyme short chain acyl-CoA dehydrogenase, which results in the inability to convert short chain fatty acids.

Very Long Chain Acyl CoA Dehydrogenase Deficiency is a type of lipid metabolism disorder, which is characterized by a deficiency of the enzyme very long chain acyl-CoA dehydrogenase. This deficiency results in the inability to convert very long chain fatty acids. Additionally, it has an exact synonym, VLCAD deficiency.

X-linked adrenal hypoplasia congenita is a type of X-linked recessive disease, adrenal cortical hypofunction, and something that at least has a material basis in some X-linked recessive inheritance. It is defined as an adrenal cortical hypofunction characterized by a reduction in adrenal gland function resulting from incomplete development of the adrenal cortex, with its material basis in the nuclear receptor NR0B1 (DAX1) gene. Additionally, it has the exact synonym congenital adrenal hypoplasia.
Herpes simplex virus keratitis is a type of keratitis, defined as a keratitis that has a material basis in herpes simplex type infection. It is also exactly synonymous with dendritic keratitis.
Cryptococcal meningitis is a type of fungal meningitis defined as a fungal meningitis that has its material basis in Cryptococcus fungal infection.
Cytomegalovirus retinitis is a type of retinitis, defined as a retinitis that has a material basis in Cytomegalovirus. It also has the exact synonym CMV retinitis.

Cutaneous candidiasis is a type of candidiasis and a skin disease that is characterized by a Candida infection located in the skin. It is identified as a condition where the disease is located in some zone of the skin.

Lupus nephritis is a type of glomerulonephritis and is also a type of condition that at least has the symptom of some inflammation. It is defined as a glomerulonephritis characterized by inflammation of the kidneys resulting from systemic lupus erythematosus.

Otulipenia is an autosomal recessive disease, which falls into the category of immune system diseases. It is characterized by several symptoms including neonatal onset of recurrent fever, erythematous rash with painful nodules, painful joints, and lipodystrophy. This condition has its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance, specifically in homozygous loss-of-function mutations in the OTULIN gene encoding a deubiquitinase with linear linkage specificity located on chromosome 5p15. Otulipenia is also known by its exact synonyms: autoinflammation, panniculitis and dermatosis syndrome, and otulin-related autoinflammatory syndrome.

Myeloid and lymphoid neoplasms with eosinophilia and abnormalities of PDGFRA, PDGFRB, and FGFR1 constitute a type of myeloid neoplasm. This myeloid neoplasm is defined by the formation of abnormal fusion genes that encode constitutively activated tyrosine kinases. It has exact synonyms, including Myeloid and Lymphoid Neoplasms with Eosinophilia and Rearrangement of PDGFRA, PDGFRB, or FGFR1, and Myeloid and lymphoid neoplasms with eosinophilia and abnormalities of platelet-derived growth factor receptor alpha (PDGFRA), platelet-derived growth factor receptor beta (PDGFRB), and fibroblast growth factor receptor-1 (FGFR1), which are recognized as a group of hematologic neoplasms.

Myeloid and lymphoid neoplasms associated with PDGFRA rearrangement are a type of myeloid and lymphoid neoplasms with eosinophilia and abnormalities of PDGFRA, PDGFRB, and FGFR1. This condition is characterized by the rearrangement of the PDGFRA gene, most often resulting in the formation of FIP1L1-PDGFRA fusion transcripts. It is exactly synonymous with Myeloid and Lymphoid Neoplasms with PDGFRA Rearrangement.

Myeloid and lymphoid neoplasms associated with PDGFRB rearrangement are a type of myeloid and lymphoid neoplasms with eosinophilia and abnormalities of PDGFRA, PDGFRB, and FGFR1. This condition is characterized by the rearrangement of the PDGFRB gene, which most often results in the formation of ETV6-PDGFRB fusion transcripts. Furthermore, it has the exact synonym "Myeloid and Lymphoid Neoplasms with PDGFRB Rearrangement."

Myeloid and lymphoid neoplasms associated with FGFR1 abnormalities represent a type of myeloid and lymphoid neoplasms with eosinophilia and abnormalities of PDGFRA, PDGFRB, and FGFR1. This condition is defined as myeloid and lymphoid neoplasms with eosinophilia and abnormalities of PDGFRA, PDGFRB, and FGFR1 that are characterized by the rearrangement of the FGFR1 gene, resulting in translocations with an 8p11 breakpoint.
Tricuspid atresia is a type of tricuspid valve disease and is defined as a tricuspid valve disease characterized by a missing or abnormally developed tricuspid heart valve at birth.
Normophosphatemic familial tumoral calcinosis is a type of calcinosis that is defined as a calcinosis characterized by massive periarticular, and seldom visceral, deposition of calcified tumors.

Esophageal atresia tracheoesophageal fistula is a type of gastrointestinal system disease characterized by the abnormal development of the esophagus and trachea, where the upper esophagus does not connect (atresia) to the lower esophagus and stomach. This may also include tracheoesophageal fistula, an abnormal connection between the esophagus and the trachea, which allows fluids from the esophagus to get into the airways and interfere with breathing. It is also known by its exact synonyms "esophageal atresia and/or tracheoesophageal fistula" and "tracheoesophageal fistula with or without esophageal atresia."

Thiopurine S-methyltransferase deficiency is a type of inherited metabolic disorder, which is characterized by significantly reduced activity of an enzyme that helps the body process drugs called thiopurines. It is also known by its exact synonyms TPMT deficiency and poor metabolism of thiopurines-1.

Bladder exstrophy epispadias cloacal exstrophy complex is a type of physical disorder characterized as a spectrum of anomalies involving the urinary tract, genital tract, musculoskeletal system, and sometimes the intestinal tract. It is also known by the exact synonym exstrophy-epispadias complex.

Bladder exstrophy is a type of bladder disease and also falls under the category of bladder exstrophy epispadias cloacal exstrophy complex. It is characterized by a specific condition that involves at least one disease located in the urinary bladder. The condition is defined as a bladder exstrophy-epispadias-cloacal exstrophy complex that features an evaginated bladder plate, epispadias, and an anterior defect of the pelvis, pelvic floor, and abdominal wall. In this condition, the rear portion of the bladder wall, known as the posterior vesical wall, turns outward (exstrophy) through an opening in the abdominal wall, and urine is excreted through this opening.
Cloacal exstrophy is a type of bladder exstrophy-epispadias-cloacal exstrophy complex, which is characterized by a defect in the urethra, bladder, and bowel.
Meningococcal meningitis is a type of bacterial meningitis characterized by having a material basis in Neisseria meningitidis infection.

Hepatic veno occlusive disease is a type of hepatic vascular disease and has a definition as a hepatic vascular disease characterized by the obstruction of some of the small veins of the liver. It also has an exact synonym, veno-occlusive disease, and an exact match MESH:D006504.

Mucositis is a type of gastrointestinal system disease characterized by painful inflammation and ulceration of the mucous membranes lining the digestive tract. This condition is also recognized for having symptoms that include some form of inflammation.
Haemophilus meningitis is a type of bacterial meningitis, defined as a bacterial meningitis that has its material basis in Haemophilus influenzae infection.

Zika virus congenital syndrome is a type of physical disorder, syndrome, and something that at least disease has basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. It is defined as a syndrome characterized in neonates by symptoms such as microcephaly, craniofacial disproportion, spasticity, seizures, irritability, and brainstem dysfunction, which includes feeding difficulties, ocular abnormalities, and findings on neuroimaging like calcifications, cortical disorders, and ventriculomegaly. This syndrome has its material basis in the acquisition of Zika virus infection in utero. Furthermore, Zika virus congenital syndrome has the exact synonym ZIKV congenital infection.

Pharc syndrome is a type of syndrome that is autosomal recessive and has its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by polyneuropathy, hearing loss, cerebellar ataxia, retinitis pigmentosa, and early-onset cataract. Additionally, pharc syndrome has an exact synonym: polyneuropathy, hearing loss, ataxia, retinitis pigmentosa, and cataract.

Mixed fibrolamellar hepatocellular carcinoma is a type of fibrolamellar carcinoma characterized by the presence of both pure fibrolamellar hepatocellular carcinoma and conventional hepatocellular carcinoma components.
Medullary colon carcinoma, which is a type of colon carcinoma, is defined as a colon carcinoma characterized by a solid growth pattern.

Mixed mucinous and nonmucinous bronchioloalveolar adenocarcinoma is a specific type of bronchioloalveolar adenocarcinoma characterized by a mixed array of different patterns, including acinar, papillary, bronchioloalveolar, and solid with mucin. It is also known by exact synonyms such as indeterminate bronchioloalveolar carcinoma and mixed mucinous and non-mucinous bronchioloalveolar adenocarcinoma.

Mucinous bronchioloalveolar adenocarcinoma is a type of bronchioloalveolar adenocarcinoma, which is defined as a bronchiolo-alveolar adenocarcinoma characterized by tumor cells that contain abundant mucin in their cytoplasm and are composed of tall columnar cells growing along alveolar walls without stromal invasion.

Nonmucinous bronchioloalveolar adenocarcinoma is a type of bronchioloalveolar adenocarcinoma that is defined as a bronchiolo-alveolar adenocarcinoma characterized by cells with cuboidal or columnar morphology with eosinophilic or clear cytoplasm, and it exhibits Clara cell or type 2 pneumocyte differentiation.

Chronic neutrophilic leukemia is a type of chronic leukemia, defined as a chronic leukemia characterized by neutrophilic leukocytosis without a detectable Philadelphia chromosome or BCR/ABL fusion gene.

Chronic myelomonocytic leukemia is a type of chronic leukemia, defined as a chronic leukemia characterized by monocytosis, increased monocytes in the bone marrow, variable degrees of dysplasia, but an absence of immature granulocytes in the blood.

Malignant hemangioma is identical to a condition that is both a cancer and derived from a hemangioblast. It is classified as a type of sarcoma and vascular cancer. Additionally, it is a type of disease that is located in the vascular system. Malignant hemangioma is defined as a cell type cancer of vascular origin, characterized by the proliferation of endothelial cells in and about the vascular lumen.

Malignant epithelioid hemangioendothelioma is a type of malignant hemangioma characterized by the presence of epithelioid endothelial cells. This condition involves neoplastic cells arranged in cords and nests, embedded in a myxoid to hyalinized stroma.

PTEN hamartoma tumor syndrome is a type of syndrome characterized as a spectrum of disorders, including Cowden syndrome, Bannayan-Riley-Ruvalcaba syndrome, PTEN-related Proteus syndrome, and Proteus-like syndrome, caused by germline mutations of the PTEN gene.

Relapsed refractory diffuse large B cell lymphoma is a type of diffuse large B cell lymphoma characterized by less than a 50 percent decrease in lesion size with induction therapy or the appearance of new lesions after the attainment of complete remission.

Superior semicircular canal dehiscence is an inner ear disease characterized by a dehiscence in the bone overlying the superior semicircular canal, leading to symptoms such as pressure or sound-induced vertigo, bone conduction hyperacusis, and pulsatile tinnitus. It is also a type of disease associated with symptoms like bone conduction hyperacusis. This condition is known by several exact synonyms, including canal dehiscence syndrome, superior canal dehiscence, superior canal syndrome, superior semicircular canal dehiscence syndrome, and third mobile window syndrome.

Carey Fineman Ziter syndrome is a type of syndrome that at least has the symptom of ptosis. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by hypotonia, Moebius sequence (bilateral congenital facial palsy with impairment of ocular abduction), Pierre Robin complex (micrognathia, glossoptosis, and high-arched or cleft palate), delayed motor milestones, and failure to thrive.

Marinesco Sjogren Syndrome is a type of autosomal recessive disease and syndrome, which has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by symptoms such as muscle weakness and progressive weakness. The syndrome is defined as a condition characterized by congenital cataracts, cerebellar ataxia, progressive muscle weakness due to myopathy, and delayed psychomotor development. Marinesco Sjogren Syndrome is also known by exact synonyms such as Garland-Moorhouse syndrome, Marinesco-Garland syndrome, Oligophrenic cerebellolenticular degeneration, and hereditary oligophrenic cerebello-lental degeneration.

Mandibulofacial dysostosis Guion Almeida type is a type of autosomal dominant disease, syndrome, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by a syndrome that includes progressive microcephaly, micrognathia, microtia, dysplastic ears, preauricular skin tags, speech delay, significant developmental delay, midface, and malar hypoplasia. Additionally, mandibulofacial dysostosis Guion Almeida type has exact synonyms which are MFDM syndrome, mandibulofacial dysostosis with microcephaly, and mandibulofacial dysostosis-microcephaly syndrome.

Congenital muscular dystrophy with cataracts and intellectual disability is a subtype of congenital muscular dystrophy and an autosomal recessive disease. This condition is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance, and it showcases symptoms such as muscle weakness and progressive weakness. Additionally, it has its disease basis in abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. Specifically, this form of congenital muscular dystrophy is defined by the onset of progressive muscle weakness in early childhood, with an autosomal recessive inheritance pattern. This is due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the INPP5K gene (607875) located on chromosome 17p13.

Infantile histiocytoid cardiomyopathy is a type of monogenic disease and an intrinsic cardiomyopathy, which means it is a kind of disease that has its basis in some gene. It is defined as an intrinsic cardiomyopathy characterized by the presence of characteristic pale granular foamy histiocyte-like cells within the myocardium, and it has its material basis in a mutation in the gene encoding mitochondrial cytochrome b.

Colorectal carcinoma is a type of carcinoma and is also a type of colorectal cancer. It is defined as a colorectal cancer that arises from the colon or rectum and invades through the muscularis mucosa into the submucosa. Furthermore, it falls under the category of something that intersects with cancer and something that at least derives from some epithelial cell.
Bilateral renal aplasia is a type of renal agenesis and is characterized by the absence of both kidneys at birth. It is disjoint with Potter's syndrome.

Peters plus syndrome is a type of syndrome characterized by anterior chamber eye anomalies, short limbs with broad distal extremities, characteristic facial features, cleft lip/palate, and variable developmental delay/intellectual disability. It is also known exactly as Krause-Kivlin syndrome, Peters anomaly-short limb dwarfism syndrome, and Peters-plus syndrome.

Adenoid cystic carcinoma is a type of carcinoma, specifically a type of tonsil cancer, and it at least derives from some epithelial cell. This type of carcinoma is associated with the pharyngeal tonsil. It is defined as an adenocarcinoma characterized by bands or cylinders of hyalinized or mucinous stroma separating or surrounded by nests or cords of small epithelial cells.
Renal hypoplasia is a type of kidney disease and is defined as a kidney disease characterized by abnormally small kidneys with normal morphology and a reduced number of nephrons.

Cakut is a type of urinary system disease characterized by structural malformations in the kidney and/or urinary tract, including vesicoureteral reflux. It has exact synonyms such as "Congenital anomalies of the kidney and urinary tract" and "Renal or urinary tract malformation."

Cakut1 is a type of CAKUT and it is defined as a CAKUT that has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the DSTYK gene on chromosome 1q32. Moreover, it has the exact synonym "Congenital anomalies of the kidney and urinary tract 1."

Cakut2 is a type of CAKUT, which is specifically defined as a CAKUT that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the TBX18 gene on chromosome 6q14. Furthermore, it is exactly synonymous with Congenital anomalies of the kidney and urinary tract 2.

@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:metabolic_dysfunction_associated_steatotic_liver_disease rdfs:subClassOf :steatotic_liver_disease ;
    :has_definition """A steatotic liver disease characterized by at least one of five cardiometabolic risk factors (adjusted for age, sex and ethnicity), alcohol consumption below 140g/week (female) or 210g/week (male), and no other discernible cause. The five cardiometabolic risk factors are:
(1) Body mass index ≥ 25 kg/m2 (adult), 23 kg/m2 (adult Asian), or 85th percentile (pediatric); waist circumference > 94 cm (adult male), 80 cm (adult female), or 95th percentile (pediatric); or ethnicity adjusted equivalents.
(2) Fasting serum glucose ≥ 5.6 mmol/L, 2-hr post-load glucose levels ≥ 7.8 mmol/L, glycated hemoglobin (HbA1c) ≥ 5.7% (39 mmol/L), type 2 diabetes, treatment for type 2 diabetes, previously diagnosed or treated type 2 diabetes (pediatric only), or serum glucose ≥ 11.1 mmol/L (pediatric only).
(3) Blood pressure ≥ lower of 130/85 mmHg or 95th percentile (age < 13 years), or 130/85 mmHg (age ≥ 13 years); or specific hypertensive drug treatment.
(4) Plasma triglycerides ≥ 1.15 mmol/L (age < 10 years) or 1.70 mmol/L (age ≥ 10 years); or lipid lowering treatment.
(5) Plasma high-density lipoprotein cholesterol ≤ 1.0 mmol/L (adult male, pediatric) or 1.3 mmol/L (adult female); or lipid lowering treatment.""" ;
    :has_exact_synonym "MAFLD",
        "MASLD",
        "metabolic dysfunction-associated fatty liver disease",
        "metabolic dysfunction-related steatotic liver disease",
        "metabolic-associated fatty liver disease",
        "nonalcoholic fatty liver disease",
        "NAFLD"@en,
        "non-alcoholic fatty liver disease"@en .
text: Metabolic dysfunction associated steatotic liver disease is a specific type of steatotic liver disease. It is defined as a steatotic liver disease characterized by the presence of at least one of five cardiometabolic risk factors (adjusted for age, sex, and ethnicity), alcohol consumption below 140g/week for females or 210g/week for males, and no other discernible cause. The five cardiometabolic risk factors include: a Body Mass Index (BMI) of ≥ 25 kg/m^2 for adults, 23 kg/m^2 for adult Asians, or at or above the 85th percentile for pediatric cases; a waist circumference greater than 94 cm for adult males, 80 cm for adult females, or at or above the 95th percentile for pediatric cases; fasting serum glucose levels of ≥ 5.6 mmol/L, 2-hour post-load glucose levels of ≥ 7.8 mmol/L, glycated hemoglobin (HbA1c) of ≥ 5.7% (39 mmol/mol), type 2 diabetes, treatment for type 2 diabetes, previously diagnosed or treated type 2 diabetes in pediatric cases, or serum glucose levels of ≥ 11.1 mmol/L in pediatric cases; blood pressure at or above the lower of 130/85 mmHg or the 95th percentile for those under 13 years of age, or 130/85 mmHg for those aged 13 years or older; plasma triglycerides levels of ≥ 1.15 mmol/L for those under 10 years of age or 1.70 mmol/L for those aged 10 years or older; and plasma high-density lipoprotein cholesterol levels of ≤ 1.0 mmol/L for adult males and pediatric cases, or ≤ 1.3 mmol/L for adult females. Additionally, metabolic dysfunction associated steatotic liver disease is exactly synonymous with a number of terms, including MAFLD, MASLD, NAFLD, metabolic dysfunction-associated fatty liver disease, metabolic dysfunction-related steatotic liver disease, metabolic-associated fatty liver disease, non-alcoholic fatty liver disease, and nonalcoholic fatty liver disease.

Sideroblastic anemia with B cell immunodeficiency, periodic fevers, and developmental delay, also known as SIFD, is a type of autosomal recessive disease that falls under the broader category of sideroblastic anemia. It is characterized by the onset of severe sideroblastic anemia in the neonatal period or infancy, stemming from autosomal recessive inheritance of homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TRNT1 gene on chromosome 3p26. This condition is also described as having a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Primary mediastinal B-cell lymphoma is a type of diffuse large B-cell lymphoma characterized by a diffuse proliferation of medium to large B-cells associated with sclerosis. It is also precisely referred to as Large cell lymphoma of the mediastinum, Mediastinal diffuse large-cell lymphoma with sclerosis, and Primary mediastinal clear cell lymphoma of B-cell type.

Nodal marginal zone lymphoma is a type of marginal zone lymphoma characterized by a marginal zone B-cell lymphoma that morphologically resembles lymph nodes involved by marginal zone lymphomas of extranodal or splenic types, albeit without evidence of extranodal or splenic disease.

Polycystic kidney disease 4 is a type of autosomal recessive polycystic kidney disease and is defined as an autosomal recessive polycystic kidney disease that has its material basis in a mutation in the PKD4 gene.

Punctate palmoplantar keratoderma type II is a type of punctate palmoplantar keratoderma, specifically an autosomal dominant disease. It is defined as a condition characterized by multiple, asymptomatic, 1 to 2 mm-long, firm, hyperkeratotic projections on the palms, soles, and digits. This type of keratoderma has its material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance.

Punctate palmoplantar keratoderma type I is a type of punctate palmoplantar keratoderma, characterized by multiple hyperkeratotic centrally indented papules that develop in early adolescence or later and are irregularly distributed on the palms and soles. It has exact synonyms, including punctate palmoplantar keratoderma type 1A and punctate palmoplantar keratoderma type 1B.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 8 (DEE8), also known as EIEE8 or Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 8, is a type of X-linked recessive disease, and it falls under the broader category of Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy. This condition is characterized by seizures that begin before the age of 2 years, severe developmental delay, and in some cases, hyperekplexia. It has a material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance, particularly stemming from a mutation in the ARHGEF9 gene located on chromosome Xq22.1.
Duodenal atresia is a type of intestinal atresia that is defined as an intestinal atresia characterized by the congenital absence or complete closure of a portion of the lumen of the duodenum.

Lysosomal acid lipase deficiency is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a lipid storage disease. It is characterized by a condition that at least has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, it is a lipid storage disease defined by dyslipidemia and the accumulation of cholesteryl esters and triglycerides within various organs, caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the LIPA gene on chromosome 10q23.31. This condition is also known as LAL deficiency or LAL-D. In terms of classifications, lysosomal acid lipase deficiency has a broader match with ICD10CM:E75.5. It has exact matches with several medical databases and classifications, including GARD:12097, OMIM:PS278000, ORDO:275761, and UMLS_CUI:C5574740.
