This disease is associated with white matter abnormalities that tend to improve with age, and in some cases, it may lead to mental retardation. The condition has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the HEPACAM gene located on chromosome 11q24. Furthermore, megalencephalic leukoencephalopathy with subcortical cysts 2b is exactly synonymous with megalencephalic leukoencephalopathy with subcortical cysts 2B, remitting, with or without mental retardation.

Megalencephalic leukoencephalopathy with subcortical cysts 2a is categorized under autosomal recessive diseases and is a specific type of megalencephalic leukoencephalopathy with subcortical cysts. It is defined by its material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. This condition is described as megalencephalic leukoencephalopathy with subcortical cysts characterized by several features, including infantile-onset macrocephaly, later onset of motor deterioration manifesting as ataxia and spasticity, seizures, cognitive decline varying in severity, and white matter abnormalities such as swelling of the cerebral white matter and subcortical cysts. These manifestations are due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the HEPACAM gene located on chromosome 11q24.

X-linked immunodeficiency with magnesium defect, Epstein-Barr virus infection, and neoplasia (XMEN) is a type of X-linked recessive disease, which falls under the category of combined T cell and B cell immunodeficiencies. This condition is characterized by a material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance. Specifically, XMEN is defined as a T cell deficiency characterized by CD4 lymphopenia, severe chronic viral infections, and defective T-lymphocyte activation in males. This is due to X-linked inheritance of mutations in the gene encoding magnesium transporter-1 (MAGT1).

The peripheral nervous system benign neoplasm, which is a type of central nervous system benign neoplasm, is defined as a central nervous system benign neoplasm that is located in the peripheral nervous system.

An autonomic nervous system benign neoplasm, which is a type of peripheral nervous system benign neoplasm, is defined as a peripheral nervous system benign neoplasm located in the autonomic nervous system.
Polycystic kidney disease is a type of cystic kidney disease that is defined by the growth of fluid-filled cysts in the kidneys. This condition reduces kidney function and may lead to kidney failure.

Pancreatic squamous cell carcinoma is a type of squamous cell carcinoma and a type of pancreatic cancer. It derives from squamous epithelial cells and is located in the pancreas. It is defined as a squamous cell carcinoma located in the pancreas.

Tuberous Sclerosis 1 is a type of Tuberous Sclerosis, characterized by hamartomas in multiple organ systems. It has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the TSC1 gene located on chromosome 9q34.

Tuberous Sclerosis 2 is a type of Tuberous Sclerosis that is defined as a condition characterized by hamartomas in multiple organ systems. It has a material basis in the autosomal dominant inheritance of a heterozygous mutation in the TSC2 gene, which encodes tuberin, on chromosome 16p13.

Familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy is a type of hypertrophic cardiomyopathy that is characterized by thickening of the heart muscle. This condition has a material basis in the autosomal dominant inheritance of one or more gene mutations.

Multinucleated neurons anhydramnios renal dysplasia cerebellar hypoplasia and hydranencephaly is a syndrome, which is also a type of autosomal recessive disease with its material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. This syndrome is specifically characterized by severe hydranencephaly with almost complete absence of the cerebral hemispheres, which are replaced by fluid, relative preservation of the posterior fossa structures, and renal dysplasia or agenesis. It is caused by an autosomal recessive homozygous mutation in the CEP55 gene on chromosome 10q23. Additionally, this condition has an exact synonym: MARCH.

Culler Jones syndrome is a type of syndrome that is also identified as an autosomal dominant disease, indicating it has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by hypopituitarism, mainly growth hormone deficiency, and/or postaxial polydactyly. This condition can also present with midline facial defects and developmental delay. It has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the GLI2 gene located on chromosome 2q14. Culler Jones syndrome exhibits incomplete penetrance and high variable expressivity.

Cold induced sweating syndrome 1 is a type of cold induced sweating syndrome. It is defined as a cold-induced sweating syndrome that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CRLF1 gene on chromosome 19p13. This condition is characterized in the neonatal period by orofacial weakness, which impairs sucking and swallowing, resulting in poor feeding that necessitates medical intervention.

Cold Induced Sweating Syndrome 2 is a specific type of Cold Induced Sweating Syndrome. It is characterized by a condition that arises due to a compound heterozygous mutation in the CLCF1 gene located on chromosome 11q13.

Cold induced sweating syndrome 3 is a type of cold induced sweating syndrome. It is defined as a cold-induced sweating syndrome that has a material basis in homozygous mutation in the KLHL7 gene on chromosome 7p15.

Bicuspid aortic valve disease is a type of aortic valve disease that is defined as an aortic valve disease characterized by the presence of an abnormal two-leaflet aortic valve in at least 2 first-degree relatives. It is also exactly synonymous with Familial bicuspid aortic valve.

Aortic valve disease 1 is a type of bicuspid aortic valve disease and an autosomal dominant disease, which specifically has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a bicuspid aortic valve disease that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the NOTCH1 gene on chromosome 9q34.

Aortic valve disease 2 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of bicuspid aortic valve disease, which at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a bicuspid aortic valve disease that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the SMAD6 gene on chromosome 15q22.

Mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 12b is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific subtype of mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome, which is characterized by its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. This condition is also noted for having symptoms including muscle weakness. Specifically, mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 12b is defined as a mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome that manifests in childhood with slowly progressive hypertrophic cardiomyopathy and generalized skeletal myopathy, leading to exercise intolerance, muscle weakness, and atrophy. This syndrome is caused by autosomal recessive inheritance of homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the solute carrier family 25 member 4 gene located on chromosome 4q35.

Mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 14 is a type of mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome and also falls under the category of conditions that have, at minimum, the phenotype of some neurodevelopmental delay. It is defined as a mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome characterized by severe lethal infantile mitochondrial encephalomyopathy and hypertrophic cardiomyopathy. This condition includes symptoms such as hypotonia and peripheral hypertonia with opisthotonic posturing, feeding difficulties, and profound neurodevelopmental delay. The material basis for this syndrome is a homozygous mutation in the OPA1 mitochondrial dynamin-like GTPase gene located on chromosome 3q29.

Mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 15 (MDDS15) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a subtype of mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome, characterized by a particular material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, MDDS15 manifests with severe intrauterine growth restriction, neonatal-onset hypoglycemia and liver dysfunction, mitochondrial DNA depletion in the liver and skeletal muscle, and abnormal mitochondrial morphology observed in skeletal muscle. The disease's genetic foundation stems from an autosomal recessive inheritance of homozygous mutation in the mitochondrial transcription factor A gene located on chromosome 10q21.

Familial erythrocytosis 3 is a type of autosomal dominant disease, primary polycythemia, and something that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a primary polycythemia that is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the EGLN1 gene located on chromosome 1q42. Furthermore, familial erythrocytosis 3 is exactly synonymous with ECYT3.

Familial erythrocytosis 4 is a type of primary polycythemia and has an exact synonym, ECYT4. It is defined as a primary polycythemia that has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance of gain-of-function mutations in the EPAS1 gene on chromosome 2p21.

Simpson Golabi Behmel Syndrome Type 2 is a type of syndrome, specifically an X-linked recessive disease, which inherently has a material basis in some X-linked recessive inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome that has its material basis in a mutation in the OFD1 gene on chromosome Xp22, characterized by developmental delay, macrocephaly, and respiratory problems.

Autosomal recessive pyridoxine refractory sideroblastic anemia 3 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, sideroblastic anemia, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a sideroblastic anemia characterized by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the GLRX5 gene on chromosome 14q32.

Blepharocheilodontic syndrome is a type of syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease, which has its material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is also known by the exact synonym Blepharo-cheilo-odontic syndrome. The syndrome is defined as one characterized by lower eyelid ectropion, upper eyelid distichiasis, euryblepharon, bilateral cleft lip and palate, and conical teeth.

Blepharocheilodontic syndrome 1 is a type of blepharocheilodontic syndrome defined as a blepharocheilodontic syndrome that has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the CDH1 gene on chromosome 16q22.

Blepharocheilodontic syndrome 2 is a type of blepharocheilodontic syndrome, defined as a blepharocheilodontic syndrome that has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the CTNND1 gene on chromosome 11q12.

Malignant pheochromocytoma is a type of adrenal medulla cancer, which is defined as an adrenal medulla cancer that arises within the adrenal medulla, releasing epinephrine and norepinephrine hormones. It is also exactly synonymous with Pheochromocytoma, malignant.

Alzheimer's disease 1 is a type of Alzheimer's disease and an autosomal dominant disease, specifically a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as an Alzheimer's disease that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the APP gene, which encodes the amyloid precursor protein, on chromosome 21q21. Additionally, Alzheimer's disease 1 is exactly synonymous with Alzheimer's disease 1, early onset.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 39 (DEE39) is a type of disorder that falls under the category of autosomal recessive diseases, developmental and epileptic encephalopathies, and is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. DEE39 is specifically defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy characterized by global developmental delay apparent in early infancy, early-onset seizures, hypotonia, poor motor function, and hypomyelination in the brain. This condition is caused by mutations in the SLC25A12 gene located on chromosome 2q31. Furthermore, developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 39 is also known by its exact synonyms: AGC1 deficiency, early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 39, and epileptic encephalopathy with global cerebral demyelination.

Retinitis pigmentosa 77 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and also a form of retinitis pigmentosa. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally has its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Furthermore, retinitis pigmentosa 77 is defined as a retinitis pigmentosa that has its material basis in a mutation in the REEP6 gene on chromosome 19p13.

CLOVES syndrome is a type of syndrome characterized by congenital lipomatous overgrowth, progressive, complex and mixed truncal vascular malformation, and epidermal nevi. This syndrome has a material basis in somatic mosaicism for postzygotic activating mutations in the PIK3CA gene on chromosome 3q26. It is also exactly synonymous with congenital lipomatous overgrowth, vascular malformations, and epidermal nevi.

X-linked chondrodysplasia punctata 2 is a type of chondrodysplasia punctata and also a type of X-linked dominant disease, which is a category of conditions that at least have a material basis in some X-linked dominant inheritance. It is defined as a chondrodysplasia punctata that has a material basis in a mutation in the gene encoding delta(8)-delta(7) sterol isomerase emopamil-binding protein on chromosome Xp11. Furthermore, X-linked chondrodysplasia punctata 2 has the exact synonyms Conradi-Hunermann Syndrome and Happle syndrome.

X-linked recessive hypophosphatemic rickets is a type of X-linked recessive disease, a type of rickets, and a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some X-linked recessive inheritance. It is defined as a rickets that has a material basis in a mutation in the CLCN5 gene on chromosome Xp11.22.

Phelan McDermid Syndrome, also known precisely as 22q13.3 Deletion Syndrome and Monosomy 22q13 Syndrome, is identified as a chromosomal deletion syndrome. Its definition encompasses a chromosomal deletion syndrome rooted in a deletion, translocation, ring chromosome formation, or other structural change of the terminal end of chromosome 22 in the 22q13 region or a disease-causing mutation of the SHANK3 gene. It is characterized by neonatal hypotonia, absent to severely delayed speech, global developmental delay, and minor dysmorphic facial features. Most instances of 22q13.3 deletion syndrome occur sporadically, with 20% of cases being autosomal dominant and inherited from a parent. The deletion predominantly happens as a random event during the formation of reproductive cells (eggs or sperm) or in early fetal development.
Hepatobiliary system cancer is a type of gastrointestinal system cancer and is defined as a gastrointestinal system cancer that is located in the hepatobiliary system.

IgG4 related disease is a type of autoimmune disease and is also characterized by having symptoms including at least some phlebitis. It is defined as an autoimmune disease that is characterized by tumefactive lesions, a dense lymphoplasmacytic infiltrate rich in IgG4-positive plasma cells, storiform fibrosis, obliterative phlebitis, autoimmune pancreatitis, and sometimes elevated serum IgG4 levels affecting various organs.

Mitochondrial complex IV deficiency nuclear type 2, also known precisely as MC4DN2 and fatal infantile cardioencephalomyopathy due to cytochrome c oxidase deficiency 1, is a type of COX deficiency infantile mitochondrial myopathy, an autosomal recessive disease, and is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. This condition is defined as a COX deficiency, infantile mitochondrial myopathy that arises from compound heterozygous mutation in the SCO2 gene located on chromosome 22q13. Additionally, Mitochondrial complex IV deficiency nuclear type 2 is accurately matched with OMIM:604377 and UMLS_CUI:C5399977.

Mitochondrial complex IV deficiency nuclear type 6, also known exactly as MC4DN6 and fatal infantile cardioencephalomyopathy due to cytochrome c oxidase deficiency 2, is a type of COX deficiency infantile mitochondrial myopathy, an autosomal recessive disease, and something that has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a COX deficiency, infantile mitochondrial myopathy that has its material basis in compound heterozygous mutation in the COX15 gene on chromosome 10q24. Furthermore, mitochondrial complex IV deficiency nuclear type 6 exactly matches OMIM:615119 and UMLS_CUI:C3554534.

Mitochondrial complex IV deficiency nuclear type 9, also known exactly as MC4DN9 and fatal infantile cardioencephalomyopathy due to cytochrome c oxidase deficiency 3, is a type of autosomal recessive disease, COX deficiency infantile mitochondrial myopathy, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a COX deficiency, infantile mitochondrial myopathy that has its material basis in homozygous mutation in the COA5 gene on chromosome 2q11. Additionally, mitochondrial complex IV deficiency nuclear type 9 has an exact match with OMIM:616500 and UMLS_CUI:C4225154.

Mitochondrial Complex IV Deficiency Nuclear Type 13 (MC4DN13), also known as Fatal Infantile Cardioencephalomyopathy due to Cytochrome C Oxidase Deficiency 4, is a type of COX Deficiency Infantile Mitochondrial Myopathy, an autosomal recessive disease, and is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. This condition is defined by a COX deficiency, infantile mitochondrial myopathy that results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the COA6 gene located on chromosome 1q42. MC4DN13 is precisely matched with OMIM:616501 and UMLS_CUI:C4225304.

Trimethylaminuria is a type of autosomal recessive disease and an inherited metabolic disorder that has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as an inherited metabolic disorder characterized by the inability to break down trimethylamine, due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the gene encoding flavin-containing monooxygenase-3 on chromosome 1q24. Additionally, trimethylaminuria has the exact synonym "fish-odor syndrome."

X-linked spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia tarda is a specific form of spinal disease, which belongs to the broader category of spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia tarda. It is also classified as a type of X-linked recessive disease, indicating its genetic inheritance pattern. This condition is characterized by its impact on the bones of the spine and the ends of long bones in the arms and legs, attributed to a mutation in the SEDL gene located on chromosome Xp22. Furthermore, it is associated with conditions that have a material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance and diseases that are located in the vertebral column and limbs.

Mitochondrial pyruvate carrier deficiency is a type of disease that falls under autosomal recessive diseases and is also categorized as a mitochondrial metabolism disease. This condition is characterized by its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, it is defined as a mitochondrial metabolism disease marked by delayed psychomotor development and lactic acidosis with a normal lactate/pyruvate ratio, which results from impaired mitochondrial pyruvate oxidation. The disease has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the BRP44L gene located on chromosome 6q27.

Malignant adenoma is a type of cell type cancer, defined as a cell type cancer that is composed of epithelial tissue in which tumor cells form glands or gland-like structures, representing an early form of colorectal cancer.
Endometrial hyperplasia is a type of uterine benign neoplasm that is defined by the excessive proliferation of the cells of the endometrium.
A desmoid tumor is a type of connective tissue benign neoplasm characterized by occurrences most often in the abdomen, arms, and legs.

Chronic eosinophilic leukemia is a type of chronic leukemia characterized by a clonal proliferation of eosinophilic precursors. This results in persistently increased numbers of eosinophils in the blood, marrow, and peripheral tissues.

Sex cord-stromal benign neoplasm is a type of reproductive organ benign neoplasm, defined as a reproductive organ benign neoplasm that arises in the ovary or testis and is composed of granulosa cells, Leydig cells, Sertoli cells, and/or fibroblasts.

Ovarian sex cord stromal tumor is a type of sex cord gonadal stromal tumor and is defined as a sex cord-gonadal stromal tumor that arises from the ovary. It is composed of granulosa cells, Sertoli cells, Leydig cells, theca cells, and fibroblasts.
An ovarian sex cord stromal benign neoplasm is a type of sex cord-stromal benign neoplasm, which is defined as a sex cord-stromal benign neoplasm that arises from the ovary.
A testicular sex cord stromal benign neoplasm, which is a type of sex cord stromal benign neoplasm, is defined as a sex cord-stromal benign neoplasm that arises from the testis.

Epithelioid inflammatory myofibroblastic sarcoma is a type of inflammatory myofibroblastic tumor and is defined as an inflammatory myofibroblastic tumor composed of epithelioid or round cells with a characteristic perinuclear or nuclear membrane staining pattern with ALK immunohistochemistry. It is frequently dispersed in myxoid stroma with prominent neutrophils or lymphocytes, and often there is an absence of plasma cells.

Epididymis disease is defined as a male reproductive system disease that is located in the epididymis. It is the same as something that intersects with a disease and something that, at the very least, has a location in the epididymis, indicating its specific association with this part of the male reproductive system.
Gastroesophageal cancer is a type of gastrointestinal system cancer, characterized by being located in the proximal esophagus and the distal stomach.

Gastroesophageal adenocarcinoma is a type of gastroesophageal cancer and also a type of adenocarcinoma. It is a specific form of cancer that is defined as a gastroesophageal cancer with a material basis in abnormally proliferating cells, derived from epithelial cells, which originate in glandular tissue. This indicates that gastroesophageal adenocarcinoma is a type of cancer that at least derives from something that intersects with epithelial cells and something that has at least some origin in a gland. Furthermore, gastroesophageal adenocarcinoma is exactly synonymous with gastric and esophageal adenocarcinoma as well as gastro-esophageal adenocarcinoma.

Trichorhinophalangeal syndrome type III, also precisely known as trichorhinophalangeal syndrome type 3, is a type of syndrome that falls under the category of autosomal dominant diseases. It is specifically characterized by sparse hair, a beaked nose, a long upper lip, and severe metacarpophalangeal shortening. This syndrome has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance and is defined through its heterozygous mutation in the TRPS1 gene on chromosome 8q23.
Peroxisomal biogenesis disorder, which is a type of peroxisomal disease, is defined as a disorder with a material basis in defects in PEX genes.

Nephrotic syndrome type 2 is a type of familial nephrotic syndrome, which is also categorized under autosomal recessive diseases. It is defined by a specific set of symptoms including steroid resistance, childhood onset of proteinuria, hypoalbuminemia, hyperlipidemia, and edema. These symptoms have a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the NPHS2 gene encoding podocin, located on chromosome 1q25-q31. Furthermore, nephrotic syndrome type 2 is precisely synonymous with steroid-resistant autosomal recessive nephrotic syndrome, highlighting its genetic inheritance pattern and resistance to steroid treatment.

Nephrotic syndrome type 5 is a familial nephrotic syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by a type that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. This syndrome is defined as a familial nephrotic syndrome that is marked by prenatal or neonatal onset of progressive renal failure accompanied by proteinuria and edema, which arises from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the LAMB2 gene located on chromosome 3p. Additionally, nephrotic syndrome type 5 has an exact synonym, which is nephrotic syndrome type 5, with or without ocular abnormalities.

Nephrotic syndrome type 13 is classified as a type of autosomal recessive disease, familial nephrotic syndrome, and is characterized as a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a familial nephrotic syndrome distinguished by an early onset of steroid-resistant nephrotic syndrome and focal segmental glomerulosclerosis, which is caused by a homozygous mutation in the NUP205 gene located on chromosome 7q33.

Nephrotic syndrome type 3 is a form of familial nephrotic syndrome that falls under the category of autosomal recessive diseases and involves conditions that invariably have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a familial nephrotic syndrome marked by an onset in early childhood, resistance to steroids, and the presence of diffuse mesangial sclerosis in most patients, resulting from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the PLCE1 gene located on chromosome 10q23. Additionally, nephrotic syndrome type 3 is precisely synonymous with early-onset nephrotic syndrome type 3.

Nephrotic syndrome type 4 is a type of autosomal dominant disease, familial nephrotic syndrome, and something that at least has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a familial nephrotic syndrome that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the WT1 gene on chromosome 11p13.

Nephrotic syndrome type 6 is classified as a type of autosomal recessive disease and a type of familial nephrotic syndrome, indicating that it has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a familial nephrotic syndrome that has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the PTPRO gene located on chromosome 12p12.

Nephrotic syndrome type 11 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a type of familial nephrotic syndrome, which is a condition that at least has its material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a familial nephrotic syndrome characterized by the onset in the first decade of life of steroid-resistant progressive renal disease, which has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the NUP107 gene on chromosome 12q15.

Nephrotic syndrome type 10 is characterized as a type of autosomal recessive disease and a type of familial nephrotic syndrome. It is also described as having a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Furthermore, it is defined as a familial nephrotic syndrome that begins in early childhood and is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the EMP2 gene on chromosome 16p13.

Nephrotic syndrome type 12 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, familial nephrotic syndrome, and something that has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a familial nephrotic syndrome characterized by an early childhood onset of steroid-resistant progressive renal failure with focal segmental glomerulosclerosis. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the NUP93 gene on chromosome 16q13.

Nephrotic syndrome type 7 is a specific form of familial nephrotic syndrome that falls under the category of autosomal recessive diseases. It is characterized by its onset in the first decade of life, leading to progressive renal disease marked by proteinuria and membranoproliferative glomerulonephritis. This condition arises due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the DGKE gene located on chromosome 17q22. It is also identified by several exact synonyms, including Ig-mediated MPGN (membranoproliferative glomerulonephritis), Immunoglobulin-mediated MPGN, and nephrotic syndrome type 7 with membranoproliferative glomerulonephritis, indicating its material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance linked to immunoglobulin mediation.

Nephrotic syndrome type 8 is a type of familial nephrotic syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease, which is also described as having a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is specifically defined as a familial nephrotic syndrome characterized by neonatal or early childhood onset, steroid-resistant renal disease that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ARHGDIA gene on chromosome 17q25.

Nephrotic syndrome type 1 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, familial nephrotic syndrome, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a familial nephrotic syndrome characterized by prenatal onset of massive proteinuria followed by steroid resistant renal disease that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the NPHS1 gene on chromosome 19q13. Additionally, it has an exact synonym: Finnish congenital nephrosis.

Nephrotic syndrome type 9 is a type of familial nephrotic syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease, which is characterized by a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a familial nephrotic syndrome marked by steroid-resistant proteinuria, hypoalbuminemia, and edema that typically begins in the first or second decade of life, stemming from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the COQ8B gene located on chromosome 19q13.

Nephrotic syndrome type 17 is a type of familial nephrotic syndrome, which is also an autosomal recessive disease, and it at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a familial nephrotic syndrome that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the NUP85 gene on chromosome 17q25.

Nephrotic syndrome type 18 is a type of familial nephrotic syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a familial nephrotic syndrome that is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the NUP133 gene on chromosome 1q42.

Nephrotic syndrome type 19 is a type of familial nephrotic syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease, which is characterized by having a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a familial nephrotic syndrome that has its material basis in a compound heterozygous mutation in the NUP160 gene located on chromosome 11p11.

Orofacial cleft 1 is a type of orofacial cleft and also falls under the category of autosomal dominant diseases, being specifically a type of condition that essentially has its material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as an orofacial cleft characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance, which arises from variation in the chromosome region 6p24.3. Additionally, orofacial cleft 1 is exactly synonymous with nonsyndromic cleft lip with or without cleft palate 1.

Orofacial cleft 2 is a type of orofacial cleft and is defined as an orofacial cleft that has its material basis in variation in the chromosome region 2p13. It also has the exact synonym nonsyndromic cleft lip with or without cleft palate 2.

Orofacial cleft 3 is a type of orofacial cleft, which is defined as an orofacial cleft that has its material basis in variation in the chromosomal region 19q13. Additionally, it has the exact synonym "nonsyndromic cleft lip with or without cleft palate 3."

Orofacial cleft 4 is a type of orofacial cleft, which is defined as an orofacial cleft that has a material basis in variation in the 4q21-q31 chromosomal region. It is also exactly synonymous with nonsyndromic cleft lip with or without cleft palate 4.

Orofacial cleft 5 is a type of orofacial cleft, which is defined as an orofacial cleft that has its material basis in a mutation in the MSX1 gene on chromosome 4p16. Furthermore, it is exactly synonymous with nonsyndromic cleft lip with or without cleft palate 5.

Orofacial cleft 7 is a type of orofacial cleft and an autosomal recessive disease. This condition is characterized by at least having a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, it is defined as an orofacial cleft that has its material basis due to a homozygous mutation in the PVRL1 gene located on chromosome 11q23. Orofacial cleft 7 is also exactly synonymous with Zlotogora-Ogur syndrome and has an exact match with the MESH code C563464.
Orofacial cleft 8 is a type of orofacial cleft, defined by having a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the TP63 gene on chromosome 3q28.
Orofacial cleft 9 is a type of orofacial cleft defined by a variation in the chromosome region 13q33.1-q34. It is exactly synonymous with nonsyndromic cleft lip with or without cleft palate 9.

Orofacial cleft 10 is a type of orofacial cleft that is defined by an orofacial cleft having a material basis in mutation in the SUMO1 gene on chromosome 2q33. It is exactly synonymous with nonsyndromic cleft lip with or without cleft palate 10.

Orofacial cleft 11 is a type of orofacial cleft defined by having a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the BMP4 gene on chromosome 14q22. It is exactly synonymous with nonsyndromic cleft lip with or without cleft palate 11.

Orofacial cleft 12 is a type of orofacial cleft that is defined as an orofacial cleft with a material basis in variation in the chromosome region 8q24.3. It also has an exact synonym, nonsyndromic cleft lip with or without cleft palate 12.

Orofacial cleft 13 is a type of orofacial cleft and an autosomal dominant disease, which is characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance that has its material basis in variation in the chromosome region 1p33 associated with enrichment of the T allele of SNP rs3827730. It is also a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance.

Orofacial cleft 14 is a type of orofacial cleft and an autosomal recessive disease that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as an orofacial cleft characterized by incomplete median clefts of both the lower lip and upper lip, double labial frenulum, and fusion of the upper gingival and upper labial mucosa. Additionally, it includes poor dental alignment and an increased interdental distance between the lower and upper median incisors.
Orofacial cleft 15 is a type of orofacial cleft that is defined by having a material basis in mutation in the DLX4 gene on chromosome 17q21.

Familial adenomatous polyposis 1 is a type of familial adenomatous polyposis and an autosomal dominant disease. It is also a type of condition that has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Furthermore, it is defined as a familial adenomatous polyposis that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the APC gene on chromosome 5q22.

Familial adenomatous polyposis 2 is a type of familial adenomatous polyposis, an autosomal recessive disease, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a familial adenomatous polyposis that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the MUTYH gene on chromosome 1p34. Additionally, familial adenomatous polyposis 2 is exactly synonymous with MUTYH-associated polyposis, MUTYH-related attenuated FAP, MUTYH-related attenuated familial adenomatous polyposis, and MUTYH-related attenuated familial polyposis coli.

Familial adenomatous polyposis 3 is a type of familial adenomatous polyposis and an autosomal recessive disease, which falls under the category of conditions that have a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a familial adenomatous polyposis characterized by having its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the NTHL1 gene located on chromosome 16p13.

Familial adenomatous polyposis 4 is a type of familial adenomatous polyposis and also falls under the category of autosomal recessive diseases. It is defined by the development of multiple colonic adenomas in adulthood, often with progression to colorectal cancer, and has its material basis in compound heterozygous mutation in the MSH3 gene on chromosome 5q11. Additionally, it is recognized as a condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 18 (DEE18), also known as early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 18, is a specific type of autosomal recessive disease, which is a subset of developmental and epileptic encephalopathies. This condition is characterized by its basis in autosomal recessive inheritance, particularly due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the SZT2 gene located on chromosome 1p34. Individuals with this condition typically exhibit a lack of developmental milestones, dysmorphic facial features, refractory seizures, and distinct brain imaging findings including a thick corpus callosum and persistent cavum septum pellucidum.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 15 (DEE15), also known as early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 15, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and falls under the broader category of developmental and epileptic encephalopathies. It is characterized by conditions that have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, DEE15 is defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy that results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the ST3GAL3 gene located on chromosome 1p34.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 23 (DEE23) is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which is a subtype of developmental and epileptic encephalopathy. This condition is defined by the onset in the first months of life of intractable seizures, severely impaired psychomotor development with poor or absent speech, cortical blindness, and dysmorphic facial features. The material basis for this disease is at least partially attributed to some autosomal recessive inheritance, specifically through homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the DOCK7 gene on chromosome 1p31. DEE23 is also precisely known by several synonyms, including Early-Onset Epileptic Encephalopathy-Cortical Blindness-Intellectual Disability-Facial Dysmorphism Syndrome, Epilepsy-Cortical Blindness-Intellectual Disability-Facial Dysmorphism Syndrome, and Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 23.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 32 (DEE32), also known as Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 32, is a type of autosomal dominant disease, which falls under the broader category of developmental and epileptic encephalopathies. It is characterized by a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, DEE32 is defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy where seizures begin between 5 and 17 months of age, leading to residual neurologic deficits. In some patients, seizures may either remit or respond to drug treatment. This condition is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the KCNA2 gene located on chromosome 1p13.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 38 (DEE38), also known as early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 38, is a type of developmental and epileptic encephalopathy and an autosomal recessive disease. This condition is characterized by a specific type that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy with seizures onset occurring between 4 and 7 months of age, severely impaired global development, hypotonia with poor head control, and visual inattention. These symptoms have a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the ARV1 gene located on chromosome 1q42.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 54 (DEE54), also known as early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 54, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific category of developmental and epileptic encephalopathy. It is characterized by delayed psychomotor development, early-onset refractory seizures, and severe intellectual disability, which arises due to a heterozygous mutation in the HNRNPU gene located on chromosome 1q44. This condition also falls under diseases that have a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 50 (DEE50) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and also falls under the broader category of developmental and epileptic encephalopathies. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, DEE50 is defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy characterized by delayed psychomotor development, early-onset seizures, severe developmental regression, and normocytic anemia, which is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CAD gene on chromosome 2p23. Additionally, DEE50 is known by several exact synonyms including CDG syndrome type Iz, CDG-Iz, Carbohydrate deficient glycoprotein syndrome type Iz, Congenital disorder of glycosylation type 1z, and early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 50.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 62 (DEE62), also known as early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 62, is categorized as a type of autosomal dominant disease and falls under the broader classification of developmental and epileptic encephalopathies. It is characterized by its onset of refractory seizures within the first weeks or months of life, accompanied by severe to profound developmental delay, hypotonia, and impaired motor and cognitive development. This condition is specifically associated with a heterozygous mutation in the SCN3A gene located on chromosome 2q24, indicating its material basis in a form of autosomal dominant inheritance.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 11 (DEE11), also known as Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 11, is a type of Autosomal Dominant disease. It falls under the broader category of Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathies, which are types of conditions that at least have a material basis in some form of Autosomal Dominant inheritance. DEE11 is defined as a Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy characterized by the infantile onset of refractory seizures, delayed neurologic development, and persistent neurologic abnormalities. This condition has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the SCN2A gene located on chromosome 2q24.

Dravet syndrome is an autosomal dominant disease, which is also a type of developmental and epileptic encephalopathy. It at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. Dravet syndrome is defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy characterized by the onset of seizures that are usually refractory to treatment in the first year of life after normal early development, and impaired psychomotor development starting around the second year of life. This syndrome has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the SCN1A gene on chromosome 2q24. Furthermore, Dravet syndrome is exactly synonymous with DEE6, DEE6A, developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 6, developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 6A, early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 6, and severe myoclonic epilepsy of infancy.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 44 (DEE44), also known as Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 44, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific kind of developmental and epileptic encephalopathy. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, DEE44 is defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy that begins in the first year of life, marked by refractory infantile spasms or myoclonus. This condition leads to developmental stagnation and severe neurologic impairment following the onset of seizures, due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the UBA5 gene located on chromosome 3q22.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 47 (DEE47), also known as Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 47, is classified as a type of autosomal dominant disease. This condition falls under the broader category of developmental and epileptic encephalopathies and is characterized by its autosomal dominant inheritance. DEE47 is defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy that presents from the first days or weeks of life, manifesting through intractable seizures, developmental regression post-seizure onset, intellectual disability, and neurologic impairment. The underlying cause of this condition is a heterozygous mutation in the FGF12 gene located on chromosome 3q28.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 63 (DEE63), also known as early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 63, is recognized as a type of developmental and epileptic encephalopathy and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by having its material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CPLX1 gene located on chromosome 4p16.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 40 (DEE40), also known as Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 40, is classified as a type of Autosomal Recessive Disease and falls under the broader category of Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathies. This specific encephalopathy is defined by having its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the GUF1 gene located on chromosome 4p12.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 45 (DEE45), also known as Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 45, is a type of autosomal dominant disease, which falls under the broader category of Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathies. This condition specifically has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy characterized by the onset in the first year of life of seizures, global developmental delay, severely impaired intellectual development, hypotonia, and other persistent neurologic deficits. The basis for this condition is a heterozygous mutation in the GABRB1 gene located on chromosome 4p13.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 24 (DEE24), also known as Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 24, is a type of autosomal dominant disease, which is a specific category of developmental and epileptic encephalopathy. This condition is characterized by its material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy that manifests in infancy with refractory seizures, severely impaired global development, intellectual disability, and behavioral abnormalities. This condition is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the HCN1 gene located on chromosome 5p12.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 65 (DEE65), also known as early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 65, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of developmental and epileptic encephalopathy. This condition is characterized by its onset in the first months to years of life, involving various types of intractable seizures, severe to profound psychomotor developmental delay, and mild facial dysmorphism. The material basis for this condition is at least partially founded in autosomal dominant inheritance and specifically involves a heterozygous mutation in the CYFIP2 gene located on chromosome 5q33.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 19 (DEE19), also known as early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 19, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of developmental and epileptic encephalopathy. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally arises from autosomal dominant inheritance. DEE19 is defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy marked by the onset of seizures within the first year of life and mild to moderate impaired intellectual development, which has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the GABRA1 gene located on chromosome 5q34.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 60 (DEE60), also known as Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 60, is classified as a type of Autosomal Recessive Disease, which falls under the broader category of Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathies. This condition is characterized by its material basis in Autosomal Recessive Inheritance. Specifically, DEE60 is defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy characterized by the onset of infantile spasms, seizures, or myoclonus within the first months of life, accompanied by hypsarrhythmia on an EEG, and severe global developmental delay. The genetic foundation of this condition is linked to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the CNPY3 gene located on chromosome 6p.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 51 (DEE51), also known as Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 51, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and falls under the broader category of developmental and epileptic encephalopathies. This condition is characterized by the onset of intractable seizures and hypotonia in the first days or weeks of life, along with severely delayed psychomotor development. The underlying cause is linked to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the MDH2 gene located on chromosome 7q11. Furthermore, DEE51 is recognized as a condition that inherently has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 61 (DEE61), also known as early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 61, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and falls under the broader category of developmental and epileptic encephalopathies. This specific condition is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Moreover, DEE61 is defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy that arises due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the ADAM22 gene located on chromosome 7q21.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 37 (DEE37), also known as early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 37, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and falls under the broader category of developmental and epileptic encephalopathies. This condition is specifically characterized by the onset of intractable seizures or abnormal movement in the first years of life and developmental delay or regression following the onset of seizures. The disorder has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the FRRS1L gene located on chromosome 9q31. Moreover, it is also described as a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 4 (DEE4), also known as early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 4, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and falls under the broader category of developmental and epileptic encephalopathies. It is characterized as a disorder that inherently has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, DEE4 is defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy with symptoms beginning with tonic seizures in early infancy and including severely impaired psychomotor development. This condition is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the STXBP1 gene located on chromosome 9q34.1.
